<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Urges Tough International Action on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Thursday called on the international community to take tough
actions over the worsening Kosovo situation after two recent mass
killings of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Blair told reporters Thursday: "It is clear that diplomatic
solution alone will not work. We have to send the strongest
possible message to (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic that
we will not tolerate any more of these atrocities."
</P>
<P>
Blair, who is attending the annual Labor Party conference in
Blackpool, noted that Britain had been calling on the
international community for months to take "more robust action in
relation to Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told BBC Radio that
Britain was seeking international community agreement for possible
armed interventions in Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Next week we get the (United Nations) report, next week if
that report makes clear that (Yugoslav President Slobodan)
Milosevic is not complying with the Security Council resolution,
then NATO is ready to act with air strikes," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"Britain is ready to act. We (are)now to seek the agreement of
the international community," Cook said, adding those possible air
attacks "may not stop in Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Yugoslav government has flatly denied any
responsibility for the killings of some 30 Albanians at two sites in
Kosovo over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In other developments, Britain announced Wednesday it would
host an urgent meeting of senior officials of the Contact Group,
including the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and
Germany in London Friday to discuss the worsening situation in
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
