<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16 GMT, October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Thursday denounced the possible use of NATO
force over Kosovo without U.N. authorization, saying that it "may
seriously aggravate the situation."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said that NATO's
intention to use force in Kosovo without permission from the
U.N. Security Council "may seriously aggravate the situation in
the region and deal a serious blow to the United Nations, the
U.N. Security Council, and the entire system of international
relations." (Russia-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Talks aimed at solving the Lesotho conflict hit
a snag Thursday, less than 24 hours before the make-or-break
rendezvous Friday between the government, opposition parties and
regional mediators.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted a source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, as saying that the ruling Lesotho
Congress for Democracy had hardened its position on certain
proposals aimed at settling the controversy over the allegations
that the May 23 general election in Lesotho was rigged.
(Lesotho-Ruling Party-Position)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli flower farmers are demanding compensation
from the Iraqi government for damages they suffered during the
Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz reported on Thursday that the Israeli
organization of flower farmers has met recently in Jerusalem with
representatives of the United Nations. (Israel-Iraq-Compensation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- Nambaryn Enhbayar, chairman of the Mongolian
People's Revolutionary Party (MPRP), called on Thursday for a
referendum to decide whether to dissolve the Great Hural
(parliament).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the autumn session of the Great Hural, which opened
here Thursday, Enhbayar, also the MPRP's parliamentary group
leader, said the Great Hural has failed to do its business for
long and so it has lost the trust of the people.
(Mongolia-Parliament-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian Prime Minister John Howard Thursday
night acknowledged that it would be a "tight finish" at Saturday's
poll.
</P>
<P>
He said this when the polling day is just one day away and he
made it clear that he would have no regrets if he lost office.
(Australia-Howard-Election) 
</P>
</TEXT>
