<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sasakawa Award Goes to Chinese Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Duo Ji Cai Rang, China's
Minister of Civil Affairs, is the winner of 1998 Sasakawa Disaster
Prevention Award, The United Nations announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The award is in recognition of his distinguished contribution
to disaster prevention, mitigation and preparedness, the U.N.
Department of Public information (DPI) in New York said in a press
release on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Angsheng of the Chinese Academy of Sciences has
been designated as co-winner of the award, it said.
</P>
<P>
The award is being presented in the wake of the worst floods
China suffered this century, which claimed over 3,000 lives.
Economic damage is estimated to reach around 30 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The award is a tribute to the work of the Chinese Government in
reducing the human and economic impact of the floods, which could
have taken a far larger toll of the country, DPI said.
</P>
<P>
Duo Ji Cai Rang has played a key role in the establishment of
China's National Disaster Reduction Plan. He also led the planning
and building of the Chinese National Center for Natural Disaster
Reduction, and the creation of a network on national disaster
information and evaluation systems.
</P>
<P>
Wang Angsheng, a scientist and member of the Chinese Institute
of Atmospheric Physics and of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, is
being recognized for his many activities to raise awareness about
the importance of natural disaster prevention and preparedness
both regionally and internationally.
</P>
<P>
The award will be presented to the winners at a ceremony at the
U.N. Office in Geneva on 14 October when World Disaster Reduciton
Day is observed.
</P>
<P>
The award, which carries a prize of 50,000 U.S. dollars, was
created in 1986. It was endowed by the then-chairperson of the
Nippon Foundation, the late Ryoich Sasakawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
