<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Not to Allow Others to Threaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Alfred
Nzo said Thursday South Africa would not allow "rogue elements"
to scupper regional efforts to build peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the South African Institute of International
Affairs in Johannesburg here, Nzo said South Africa was not
prepared to allow the violent overthrow of the Lesotho
government.
</P>
<P>
"We were not willing to stand by... and see certain groups in
Lesotho refuse to explore all possible means of dispute
resolution, rather trying to win enough time to violently
overthrow the government," said Nzo when explaining Pretoria's
role in a military intervention in Lesotho last week.
</P>
<P>
"There is no greater threat to our collective efforts to build
peace and prosperity than these types of rogue elements," Nzo
said, noting that South Africa would act in an appropriate manner
in response to each situation that arose.
</P>
<P>
An 800-strong troops from South Africa and Botswana entered
Lesotho on September 22 at the invitation of Lesotho Prime
Minister Pakalitha Mosisili to help restore law and stability in
the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho was in turmoil since early August, and its government
became paralyzed in mid-September when opposition parties and
mutinous soldiers in the country claimed the May 23 general
election was rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy.
</P>
<P>
Nzo pointed out that human rights and democracy would not
automatically bring a better world. For these principles to
flourish, an environment of peace was required.
</P>
<P>
He said that South Africa would "continue to fight for the
transformation of international relations so as to eradicate
aggression, the usurping of power,... foreign occupation, and the
use force." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
