<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Party Chief Meets Japan's Business Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Communist Party chief Le
Kha Phieu Thursday met President of Japan's Union of Economic
Organizations (Keidanren) Tadashi Imai and his entourage, who are
visiting here to boost investment and trade relations with
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
According to Vietnam News Agency, Phieu, general secretary of
the ruling Communist Party, hoped that Japan will continue
providing Vietnam with official development assistance and
boosting investment in and cooperation with the country,
especially in the fields of agriculture, forestry and fishery.
</P>
<P>
Phieu also hoped that his country and Japan will exchange
experiences in the fields of finance, banking and personnel
training.
</P>
<P>
Imai said reportedly that although Japan is facing economic
difficulties, its 500 establishments, companies and businesses
operating in Vietnam wish to maintain and develop their trade
cooperation with the country.
</P>
<P>
While in Vietnam, the Japanese economic delegation is scheduled
to have working sessions with the Ministry of Planning and
Investment and meet the country's President Tran Duc Luong and
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Vietnam's biggest trading partner and official
development assistance provider. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
