<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Announces Plan for Troops Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine is going to cut 50,000
troops this year and 20,000 troops next year, Ukrainian Defense
Minister Oleksandr Kuzmuk announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under an order by Ukrainian President and Commander-in-chief
Leonid Kuchma, Ukraine's army will be reduced to 420,000 by
December 31, 1998, including 320,000 soldiers and 100,000 office
workers. By the end of 1999, the total number will be reduced to
400,000, reported the Interfax-Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian military also plans to further cut the army to
350,000 by the end of 2005, in line with its development and
construction program, Kuzmuk added.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the year, Ukraine had an army and support
staff composed of 470,000 people, which includes 360,000 soldiers
and 110,000 functionaries.
</P>
<P>
The reductions will help the Ukrainian army resolve some
problems such as a shortage of cash for military expenditures, and
problems in war preparedness and logistic support, said Kuzmuk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Reiterates "One China" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian minister Thursday
reiterated his government's continued observance of "one China"
policy and hoped that the two states would strengthen their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At a reception held in the Chinese Embassy here, Zambian
Minister of Labor and Social Security Peter Machunggwa spoke
highly of the "excellent and warm relations" that China and
Zambia have enjoyed in the past decades.
</P>
<P>
"China and Zambia enjoy excellent and warm relations dating
back to Zambia's pre-independence days," said Machunggwa at the
gathering to celebrate China's 49th National Day which falls on
today or October 1.
</P>
<P>
Machunggwa noted that the relations between China and Zambia
have grown tremendously in recent times, especially in political
and economic fields.
</P>
<P>
He also praised China's peace efforts, saying that China has
always stuck to positions which are consistent with global
efforts aimed at safeguarding world peace.
</P>
<P>
At the National Day reception which attracted over 200
diplomats, local officials and businessmen, Chinese Ambassador
Wang Yunxiang described China and Zambia as "all weather
friends".
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the development of the bilateral relations has
gained new momentum since Zambian President Frederick Chiluba's
visit to China in 1993 and former Chinese Premier Li Peng's visit
to Zambia in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade between the two countries increased 140
percent in 1997 over the previous year and the Chinese direct
investment in Zambia has soared up to 30 million U.S. Dollars,
according to the Chinese ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Wang also briefed the guests on China's recent decisive
victory over the severe floods in southern and northern part of
the country which caused heavy losses in lives and properties.
</P>
<P>
He said the victory has proved once again that the Chinese
nation has a highly strong cohesive force during a hard time and
that the Chinese nation is "invincible". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
