<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to cut the customs tariffs of
electrical appliances by 10 percent to a maximum 40 percent, the
Al Ahram daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on trucks, table, kitchen utensils and sanitary
appliances will be reduced by 5 percent. Those on electric lamps,
cables and transformers will be slashed by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Finance Ministry has said the cuts of tariffs are
in conformity with international obligations and aimed at
liberalizing trade and relieving the burdens of the citizens. its
foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt started Thursday to impose customs tariffs and
sales taxes on the diplomatic cars coming from abroad for
diplomats working in Egypt, the Egyptian Al Akhbar daily reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, duties and car license fees will be collected on
cars bought from diplomats.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Suez Canal Authority made a revenue of 1.76
billion U.S. dollars last year, the Egyptian Alam Al Yom daily
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Minister of Agriculture Mejhim Khreisha said
on Wednesday that the arable land in the Arab world stands at 167
million hectares, less than 28 percent of which is cultivated for
agriculture, the Jordan Times reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a meeting entitled "Increased Production and
Productivity," Khreisha said that 84 percent of the land for
agriculture depends on rain water and the rest on irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The irrigated land concentrates in Egypt, Sudan and Iraq, he
added.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Minister of Water and Irrigation and
Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Hani Malki said on
Wednesday that the kingdom has initiated a project worth 20
million Jordanian dinars (28 million U.S. dollars) to develop an
area to the south of the Dead Sea into a tourist resort aimed at
providing tourists with quality services.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The official Kuwaiti Economic Development Fund
has loaned 30 million dollars to Pakistan for rebuilding a power
plant in Punjab, central Pakistan, the Kuwaiti News Agency reported
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The loan with a 3 percent interest rate should be repaid in 21
years with a six-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti fund has provided Pakistan with 13 loans worth more
than 222 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the official Kuwaiti Investment Institution offered
a 250-million-dollar loan to Pakistan in August to help enhance
its foreign exchange reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
