<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Calls for Extended Cease-fire in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) called Thursday for a six-month
Extension of the cease-fire in Sudan and its inclusion of
provinces beside Bahr el Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here by UNICEF's Addis Ababa Office
said the three-month cease-fire between the Sudanese Government
and the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) must be
extended in time and broadened in scope.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire expires on October 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The release said, the cease-fire enabled the humanitarian
community to address the acute crisis in southern Sudan, adding
as this opportunity will end now, the result would be continued
sufferings for the nation as a whole and for the children and
women of southern Sudan in particular.
</P>
<P>
It said, "a prolonged cease-fire must include all areas of
southern Sudan and be seen as a step toward a permanent political
settlement -- so that the civilian population can escape a
continuation of the famine and war-related carnage that have
ravaged their lives."
</P>
<P>
UNICEF, as the leading U.N. agency which has an office in
southern Sudan, is engaged in a wide range of humanitarian
activities in the country, the release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Washington Talks: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat said on Thursday that progress was made during a three-way
summit in Washington early this week over the long-delayed Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks in Gaza upon returning from Cairo,
where he briefed Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on his meeting
with the United States President Bill Clinton and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu last Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait and see until the next meeting which will take
place between me and Netanyahu and (U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine) Albright," Arafat said, referring to a question whether
he expects an agreement to be signed in the near future for the
Israeli troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due to visit the Middle East next week to prepare
for another three-way summit in Washington in the middle of the
month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to hand over another
13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in return for
crackdown on Islamic militants by Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the proposal, but Israel has
not, citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that it would hand over 10 percent of the West
Bank to the Palestinians and turn the rest 3 percent into a nature
reserve, in which the Palestinians would have limited
administrative power.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeina, Arafat's senior adviser, told Voice of
Palestine radio on Thursday that the gap between Israel and the
Palestinians over the Israeli withdrawal "still exists and it is
big."
</P>
<P>
But he said that in the coming two weeks, the U.S. will make a
new round of mediation in the region and that "it will be an
opportunity to get a breakthrough." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
