<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Peace Hampered by Arms Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of rival Northern Irish
parties on Thursday failed to end a disarmament stalemate that has
hampered the province's peace process.
</P>
<P>
After 75 minutes of talks, First Minister David Trimble said he
hoped Irish republican chief Gerry Adams would help his IRA
guerrilla allies face up to the need for scrapping arms. The Irish
Republican Army has spurned all such demands, according to
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
Adams countered that pro-British stalwart Trimble should press
ahead with setting up structures to give Sinn Fein its first-ever
role in running the British province.
</P>
<P>
"We did have a good discussion. There obviously hasn't been a
breakthrough but I don't think anyone expected it," Reuters quoted
Adams as saying after his third round of talks with Trimble in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
But the talks were called "useful" and were expected to
continue.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to work at it. If there is a political will
to resolve this within the context of the Agreement, then it can
be done," Adams said.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, who leads the powerful Protestant Ulster Unionist
Party (UUP), and Adams, whose Sinn Fein party draws support among
Catholics supporters of Irish unity, negotiated the Good Friday
Agreement along with other political groups in April in a bid to
end years of conflict over the future of British rule.
</P>
<P>
But a wrangle over long-standing demands for the IRA and
pro-British "loyalist" militias to disarm is delaying progress on
the formation of structures that are part of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Combatants called ceasefires which paved the way for agreement
on a new administration in which Protestants and Catholics would
share power in Belfast and creation of links with Dublin to
promote a new era of island-wide co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Trimble insisted that the IRA dismantles its vast armouries
before Sinn Fein gets a seat on the new institutions.
</P>
<P>
"There is a failure to realize on the part of Sinn Fein that
decommissioning (disarmament) is actually part of the Agreement,"
Trimble was quoted by Reuters as telling reporters.
</P>
<P>
"All of society is calling for this to happen and the problem
arises because a small element within the republican movement
can't face up to its responsibilities...I hope Mr Adams can help
them," the UUP leader said.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners are being freed early as part of the peace deal and
Britain has also reduced its military presence. The accord also
calls for arms decommissioning within two years.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein accuses unionists of trying to make early disarmament
a precondition of republicans' entry to government.
</P>
<P>
"There is at the moment a quite clear difference of
interpretation about what is in the Agreement," Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
The British and Irish governments are anxious that Trimble and
Adams quickly narrow the gap in time to meet an October 31 target
for action on all-Ireland co-operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
