<HEADLINE> Israeli Airline Admits Carrying Nerve Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) - - Israeli El Al airline
confirmed on Thursday that its cargo plane that crashed in
Amsterdam six years ago was carrying the chemical used to produce
the deadly sarin gas.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, El Al spokesman
Nachman Klieman said that the plane was carrying dimethyl
methylphosphonate, a key component of sarin, when it crashed
into an apartment block and killed 43 people.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after a Dutch newspaper reported early this
week that the El Al plane was carrying 190 litters of dimethyl
methylphosphonate.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the Chemical was transported to
the Institute for Biological Research in the Tel Aviv suburb
of Ness Ziona to make chemical and biological weapons there.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Transport Ministry spokesman Avner Ovadiah said on
Thursday that though there was nothing new in the Dutch
newspaper's report, Israel's Civil Aviation Authority will look
into it.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it will not be a new investigation of the
crash but only a check into the specific claim about nerve gas
components.
</P>
<P>
The airline spokesman claimed that immediately after the
accident Israel handed over the cargo manifest to the Dutch
government, on which the name of the chemical was listed.
</P>
<P>
Klieman also noted that the chemical dimethyl
methylphosphonate, which can also be used as a flame retardant
and in the manufacture of plastic, is approved for transport on
both passenger and cargo planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
