<HEADLINE> Schroeder to Be Confirmed as German Chancellor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder, who defeated
Chancellor Helmut Kohl in Germany's general elections last Sunday,
is set to be formally elected as chancellor by parliament on
October 27, officials of his Social Democratic Party (SPD) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agenda worked out on Thursday by leaders of the SPD
and its potential coalition partner, the Greens, the two parties
plan to wind up their negotiations to form a center-left coalition
government by October 23.
</P>
<P>
Should the SPD and the Greens be able to agree on a coalition,
the new German Bundestag (lower house of parliament), in which the
SPD and the Greens together will hold a 21-seat majority, is due
to convene its first session on October 26 and will formally elect
Schroeder as chancellor the day after.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from an informal coalition talks between the SPD and
Greens, Schroeder told reporters that the talks had proceeded in a
"friendly atmosphere" and both sides agreed to push forward the
negotiations swiftly.
</P>
<P>
According to Schroeder, the distribution of future cabinet
posts, a potential bone of contention, has not been discussed
Thursday. "We have to agree upon a solid and financible common
program at first," he said.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and Greens, both in opposition in the past 16 years,
broadly agree on economic and social issues, including job
creation, tax reforms and immigration policy. However, the SPD
could have great difficulties to tackle some radical demands from
the Greens like the shutdown of nuclear power plants and its
opposition to the NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has said that he would pursue the coalition
negotiations to form a stable government under the guidelines of
"economic stability, social order and continuity in foreign
policy".
</P>
<P>
Under the current agenda, Schroeder will not represent Germany
at the European Union summit on October 24-25 in Portschach,
Austria. Kohl, who acts as a caretaker during the transitional
period, has made clear he would not attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
German press reports quoted government sources as saying that
Germany is mostly likely to be represented at the EU summit by the
incumbent foreign minister and vice-chancellor Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
