Congolese President Laurent Kabila captured Punia town Wednesday,
Rwanda News Agency reported in Kigali Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Punia town is located 200 km north of Kindu, a key base for
Kabila's loyalist forces and their allies targeted by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Rebel-controlled radio Bukavu Thursday quoted a senior rebel
commander as claiming that a whole company of Kabila's troops
surrendered and joined the rebel side.
</P>
<P>
Tutsi-led rebels took up arms to fight Kabila since August 2
and their offensive in the west was routed by allied forces of
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia. Kabila accuses Rwanda and Uganda of
invading to back the rebels but the two countries deny direct
involvement.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa and Bangui Wednesday confirmed Chadian troops are at
present in Congo (K) to help Kabila to cope with the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebels have condemned France for not having
intervened to stop Chad from sending troops to prop up Kabila,
radio Bukavu said.
</P>
<P>
Chad dispatched about 1,000 soldiers to help Kabila in his war
against the rebels in the east of the country. 
</P>
