<HEADLINE> Blair's Visit to Bejing Marks New Chapter, Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, England, October 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime
Minister Tony Blair's upcoming visit to Beijing "marks a new
chapter in British-Chinese relations," a Downing Street spokesman
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which begins on October 6, "comes at a time when
bilateral relations with China have been never so good," said
Blair's chief spokesman Alistare Campbell at a news briefing in
Blackpool, a coastal city in northwestern England where the annual
Labor Party Conference is holding.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said the bilateral relations are no longer plagued by
the difficult past after Hong Kong was handed over to China last
year and the successful transition of Hong Kong has proved that
pesimism was wrong.
</P>
<P>
"Britain has also been struck by the new responsibility that
China is showing to the global financial crisis and the prime
minister believes the way is now open to Britain to forge a new
partnership relations with China," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On the purpose of the visit, Campbell said Blair will first of
all use the visit to expand a deepened relationship with China on
some specific international issues such as financial crisis,
crimes and drugs, terrorism, nuclear proliferation, global poverty
and environment.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the prime minister will strengthen commercial and
economic ties with China. Blair will be accompanied by a
substantial senior business delegation which will sign some
important contracts with China.
</P>
<P>
Blair also hopes to take the chance to further strengthen his
personal relationship with his Chinese counterpart Zhu Rongji, of
whom Blair has a great deal of admiration, according to Campbell.
</P>
<P>
"We are cooperating far more closely on the above-mentioned
issues and are building a modern relationship with China that is
very much looking forward to the 21 century rather than back to
the days of British Empire," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations between Britain and China have achieved
remarkable progress since Labor took power in May of last year,
with frequent exchange of visits of senior officials of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In the commercial fields, according to Campbell, Britain's
trade with China rose by 15 percent in 1997, with export to China
increasing by 26 percent. Besides, Britain is Europe's leading
investor in China, to the amount of 5.3 billion U.S. dollars by
the end of last year, with another 8 million dollars on the way.
</P>
<P>
Britain's cooperation and exchange with China on cultural,
scientific, law and sports fields are also progressing, Campbell
added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the British prime minister believes that
under Zhu's determined leadership, China is prepared to push very
radical reform in its bid to emerge as a great power in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Although the domestic challenges are enormous, Campbell said,
"China is showing responsibility and willingness to play a leading
role" in economic stage in the world community.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said Blair speaks highly of China's commitment not to
devaluate its currency RMB, saying that "has played a very
important part in avoiding even worse financial instability in the
region."
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister also believes that Britain and the West
have got to respond boldly and positively toward what China has
got to do, help them make the transition that they are trying to
make in the process of forging a new and more positive partnership
between East and West," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
