<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia to Take Unpopular Measures in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said on Thursday that the Russian government might to
take "unpopular steps" to get out of the current crisis, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After a government meeting held on Thursday Primakov told
reporters that Russia was counting on the release of a new tranche
of International Monetary Fund, but if it was suspended or
canceled, the government "has to take measures, which may be
rather unpopular."
</P>
<P>
According to him, if the IMF releases a 4.3-billion-dollar
tranche, Russia could be able to get out of the current adverse
situation with minimum losses.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that the IMF "must take into consideration the
fact that up till today we have been working according to its
recommendations."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also noted that a Russian delegation is to
fly to Washington on October 2 for talks with the IMF. "We expect
that the IMF will give Russia the promised tranche, with the help
of which we want to launch the mechanism of getting out of the
current critical situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Denying the rumours about the government promoting a bill,
which provided for a state monopoly in the sphere of currency
circulation, Primakov said foreign currency will be freely sold
and purchased in Russia.
</P>
<P>
He spelled out the most important steps that the government is
planning to take to pull the country out of the financial and
economic crisis. These are, in particular, designed to stabilize
the ruble, rather than the whole program, he said.
</P>
<P>
The banking system should be normalized, and the prices of
natural and local monopoly products will be regulated, while the
state machinery must be strengthened, according to the premier.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the World Bank promised to provide to Russia
22.6 billion U.S. dollars as a package of financial aid in this
summer. By now, only part of the sum has been sent to the
economic-desolated country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
