<HEADLINE> EC to Propose Working Time for Mobile Road Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Thursday that it now had to propose a working time for the mobile
road transport sector of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation union, said
that it would rapidly prepare proposals for legislation after the
labor and management in the mobile road transport sector failed to
reach agreement on their own.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to prepare proposals on working time
for truck, coach and taxi drivers or what the commission has
described as the mobile road transport.
</P>
<P>
European Employment Commissioner Padraig Flynn and Transport
Commissioner Neil Kinnock said Thursday in a joint statement: "The
social partners have passed up an important opportunity to resolve
the key issues that have provoked uncertainty and unrest in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
"We are greatly disappointed that the health and safety
benefits secured in the rail and maritime sectors could not be
extended to road transport."
</P>
<P>
The commissioners welcomed the signature by the social partners
in the railway and maritime industries of agreements on working
time in their sectors which will be converted into commission
proposals to the European council of ministers for EU legislation.
</P>
<P>
French truck drivers staged a one-day strike earlier last month
to demand shorter working hours.
</P>
<P>
The commission urged the parties concerned to strive for an
accord on working time but the social partners failed to come out
with an agreement in their meeting on September 18.
</P>
<P>
The commission then set September 30 as the deadline for the
social partners to work out their solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The commission has already worked out a regulation on working
time for the non-mobile road transport sector in July last year.
</P>
<P>
There are approximately 3.5 million people involved in the road
transport industry in the European Union. The total includes both
the non-mobile and mobile transport workers.
</P>
<P>
French truckers launched a multi-day strike earlier this year
prior to the World Cup soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
The strike caused a road transport havoc and presented a
blockade to the inter-European community trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
