<HEADLINE> Annan to Present Report on Kosovo Early Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is expected to present his report on Kosovo to the
Security Council "as soon as possible early next week," U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This report would be presented to the 15-member council most
probably on Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed the time framework for his report presentation
in his meeting with both the outgoing and incoming presidents of
the Security Council on Wednesday evening, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Succeeding Hans Dahlgren of Sweden, Britain's U.N. Ambassador
on Thursday became the council president for the month of October.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks just hours before an emergency
meeting by the Security Council to consider how to respond to
recent reports of massacre in Kosovo, Serbia's province of mainly
ethnic Albanians within the jurisdiction of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia (FRY).
</P>
<P>
The remarks also coincided with NATO's completion of a plan for
possible air strike on Serbian security forces and the withdrawal
of Serbian forces into their barracks at the end of their
anti-terrorist campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In Geneva on Thursday, United Nations High Commissioner for
Human Rights chief Mary Robinson called for an independent inquiry
into the "reprehensible" massacre of 30 civilians in central
Kosovo last weekend allegedly carried out by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
"These killings are particularly reprehensible because they
are evidence that despite expressions of international concern
and official assurances that civilians would be respected,
atrocities are continuing in Kosovo," she said in a statement
from her office at Geneva.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Annan, in a statement issued through his
spokesman's office, voiced his "outrage" at the reported
massacre in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians, who form a majority of
the province's population of 2 million, have been battling with
Serbians for independence since February this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovnovic told a
press conference here earlier this week that the international
community lacks comprehensive and fair information on Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
