<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Continuation of UNIKOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday recommended that the
United Nations Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission (UNIKOM) be
maintained.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on UNIKOM, the Secretary-General said that
during the past six months, the mission, which is monitoring the
demilitarized zone along the Iraq-Kuwait border, continued to
contribute to the maintenance of calm and stability in the zone.
</P>
<P>
"The situation along the border was generally quiet." Annan
said, adding that UNIKOM received cooperation of the Kuwait and
Iraqi authorities in discharging its duty.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, UNIKOM carried out its normal
operation without interruption, Annan said in the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the number of violations in the
demilitarized zone dropped by more than fifty percent.
</P>
<P>
UNIKOM continued to dispose of unexploded mines and bombs in
the demilitarized zone, with a total of 5,823 unexploded devices
destroyed, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
