<HEADLINE> 30 Tons of Tomatoes Rotten at Akomadan, Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 tons of
tomatoes produced by growers are getting rotten at Akomadan,
Ghana due to lack of marketing facilities, Ghana News Agency
(GNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The famers said they are getting good harvests as a result of
the correct application of modern scientific methods of farming
and planting of improved tomato seeds given by the Akomadan
Irrigation Development Authority (IDA) and the Ministry of Food
and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Peter Obeng-Dabo, Offinso District Director of Food and
Agriculture said if farmers are not given an encouraging price
immediately, it will not only affect them financially but also
dampen their spirits to stop embarking on large-scale production
in future.
</P>
<P>
He said the local IDA has about 1,000 hectares but only 64.7
hectares have been cultivated with tomatoes due to financial
constraints.
</P>
<P>
Mr Obeng-Dabo said the establishment of processing and
preservation facilities in and around the project area will
enable small holders to benefit from their labor.
</P>
<P>
The farmers appealed to the government to establish a tomato
factory at Akomadan and to re-introduce subsidies on agricultural
inputs like spraying machines and insecticides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
