<HEADLINE> Ghanaian Authorities close down Varsity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Authorities have closed down
the University of Science and Technology (UST) in Kumasi
following a violent demonstration by the students Wednesday
night, Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Academic Executive Council has ordered immediate closure
of the University after an emergency meeting Thursday "to protect
life and property... All the students were expected to leave
campus by 14:00 hours today (Thursday)." Ambrose Tuah, acting
Vice-Chancellor of the school, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Tuah said the students damaged the bungalows of the Acting
Vice-Chancellor and some lecturers.
</P>
<P>
He described as "flimsy" complaints by the students that the
university authorities had asked three students to sleep in a
room in the main halls of residence, while those in the annex are
paired.
</P>
<P>
"This is not enough to warrant vandalism.. I'd want to believe
that there is more to it," the acting Vice Chancellor said and
added that further investigation would be conducted into the
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Police sources told journalists that at about 20:45 hours
Thursday about 150 students, wearing red bands and armed with
clubs marched through the campus and caused some damage to the
bungalows.
</P>
<P>
They destroyed the source of water supply to lecturer's
bungalows. Louvre blades, flower pots, mosquito nets, water
meters and pens for sheep and goats were not spared, police
inspector Arthur said.
</P>
<P>
Inspector Arthur said there had been no arrest and no
casualties.
</P>
<P>
The students and Education authorities have had disagreements
over payment of new fees for residential accommodation leading to
a series of demonstration in the capital, Accra.
</P>
<P>
However, at the beginning of the academic year which opened in
September, the school authorities tied admission to the payment
of 150,000 Cedis (Some 65 U.S. Dollars) which the students paid
but reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
Government said it was introducing the "user fees" to provide
accommodation for the students. Hitherto, at least four students
share one room in campus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
