<HEADLINE> Zambia reaches trade Pact With SACU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has finally reached a
trade agreement with the Southern African Customs Union (SACU),
Zambian Commerce, Trade and Industry Minister David Mpamba said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister told a German business delegation that the only
step remaining is for each government of the SACU member
countries to sign and ratify the agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said once signed, the agreement will level the playing
field in terms of trade between Zambia and the SACU member
countries, especially South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba also urged German investors to come and invest in his
country, saying Zambia has put in place various incentives for
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion George Chabwera, chairman of the Zambia
Association for Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI) said
investment confidence is at the lowest in Zambia now because of
various economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
He said inflation and interest rates are on the rise and
Zambia's currency has continued to fall in value against other
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The national debt has made the government incapable of
financing development projects and providing basic needs for
Zambians.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the problems to the policies of the
International monetary Fund (IMF) which do harm to Zambia's
economy.
</P>
<P>
German business delegation leader Jens peter Breitengross said
his delegation has come to find out the economic situation
despite having heard so many negative things.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of political and economic stability
for foreigngross investments to be put in Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
