<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandans Observe Heroes' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A rally and other ceremonies
were held at the National Heroes' cemetery in Remera, near the
national Amahoro Soccer Stadium to commemorate the National
Heroes Day which falls on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The festivities marking the day were officiated by Rwandan
president Pasteur Bizimungu, and Vice-President and Defense
Minister, Major General Paul Kagame, assisted by senior
government civil and military officials, foreign diplomats, heads
of religious denominations, and residents of the capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the day was the laying of wreaths of flowers
on two graves, one belonging to late Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA)
commander, Major General Fred Gisa Rwigema, and the other
dedicated to the Unknown Soldier, Rwanda News Agency (RNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
October first is an important date in the history of Rwanda.
It actually marked the beginning of the struggle for liberation
launched by the RPA which was fighting to remove the former
regime which had denied more than one and a half million
Rwandans, mainly Tutsis their repatriation back to the country.
</P>
<P>
Major Fred Rwigema initiated the struggle, but died in the
early days of October 1990. His ideals were taken up by freedom
fighters who pursued the struggle and later drove out the
''genocidaire''regime in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Fred Rwigema is also best recalled for his pan-Africanist
ideals. He fought for the liberation of Mozambique alongside late
president Samora Machel and his Front for the Liberation of
Mozambique (FRELIMO) from the yoke of Portuguese colonists.
</P>
<P>
He was among the top military commanders of the National
Resistance Army in NRA's struggle against the dictatorship in
Uganda which swept to power president Yoweri Museveni in 1986.
</P>
<P>
It is in memory of late Fred Gisa Rwigema, and all the
soldiers who gave their lives on the battlefield, as heroes that
today's ceremonies were held.
</P>
<P>
In his address at the rally, Rwandan Minister of Culture
Jacques Bihozagara underlined that while commemorating the event,
all national heroes, ''those of the past, those who liberated
Rwanda, those who fought the genocide, those of history and
culture, those of economy,'' should be remembered.
</P>
<P>
President Pasteur Bizimungu in his speech reminded that Rwanda
was liberated because of the heroic acts of national heroes, and
that Rwandans should move into their foot steps so as achieve
total liberation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
