<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Form Department for Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon announced a plan on
Thursday to set up a special state department aimed at handling
affairs of the country's 230,000 elderly people.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference marking the International Day for the
Elderly, Director General of the Social Affairs Ministry Nehmat
Kenaan said the government intends to turn the non-governmental
National Association for the Elderly into a state authority under
the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Five committees will be formed under the association founded
last year and financed by the country's billionaire prime
minister, Rafik Hariri, Kenaan said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the committees are to conduct studies and surveys
on the old citizens, provide them with services, draft related
laws and launch campaigns to raise national awareness to respect
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The elderly above age 64 in Lebanon are estimated at 6.85
percent of the whole population and the proportion is expected to
rise to 13 percent in the year of 2025.
</P>
<P>
Kenaan said the status of Lebanon's elderly in general is good
since "family ties are still strong."
</P>
<P>
But, the current economic hardships are depriving some of the
elderly of the basic medical and social help.
</P>
<P>
Kenaan called for close cooperation between official and
private sectors in securing better life for the advanced
citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
