<HEADLINE> Canadian Minister Outlines Cryptography Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are free to develop,
import and use whatever cryptography products they wish, according
to a cryptography policy outlined by Industry Minister John Manley
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government will not implement mandatory key recovery
requirements or licensing regimes, Manley said.
</P>
<P>
Cryptography is a set of technologies used to provide security
for electronic transmissions and of information stored on computer
systems and networks such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The new policy is an essential part of Canada's electronic
commerce strategy designed to make Canada a world leader in the
use of electronic commerce by the year 2000, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, Canada will continue to implement
cryptography export controls in keeping with the framework of
international agreements, while taking into consideration of the
export practices of other countries.
</P>
<P>
"This policy is good for Canadian economy...It supports the
increased use of electronic commerce products and services in
Canada, as well as the export of Canadian information technology
to other countries," Manley said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure public safety, the Canadian government also proposes
amendments to the country's criminal code to criminalize the
wrongful disclosure of keys and deter the use of encryption in
crimes and cryptography in evidence concealing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camdessus Urges More Bolder Actions to Spur Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) here, Thursday
urged world powers to do more to spur economic growth and halt a
spreading economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
While briefing reporters prior to the IMF-World Bank joint
annual meetings of the 182-nation financial institutions, he said
the world's seven richest countries must push for stronger growth
to offset steep recessions in many Asian nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
He endorsed the U.S. Fed's recent decision to cut a key U.S.
interest rate by a quarter-point and suggested that European
monetary authorities should take similar steps.
</P>
<P>
When asked why stock markets, particularly in the United
States, have reacted so negatively to the Fed rate cut, the IMF
chief said he believes confidence will soon be restored if
financial leaders take clear decisions during the upcoming
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 finance ministers and the central bank governors are
scheduled to meet Saturday. Camdessus said the discussions should
focus on ways to improve timely release of key economic data so
the IMF and investors can better spot troubles and a review of
proposals to upgrade banking regulation.
</P>
<P>
"If we want to make the world a better place, then we have to
go for transparency, go for strengthening of financial and banking
systems and the orderly integration of emerging markets into the
world economy," Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
As the financial crisis triggered off in Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia and South Korea and recently rocked Russia and even
posing a threat to Latin America, the IMF took the lead in
launching a rescue package of over 100 billion U.S. dollars for
the affected nations.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus insisted that the IMF monitored the financial chaos
in the early stage and took proper actions at the time. But he
conceded that the speed of the spreading crisis has surprised him.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of the virus was so strong and so quick in so many
places," he said. "We did not see... how the crisis in Russia
could prompt the lack of confidence in Latin America two weeks
later."
</P>
<P>
The threat that the current turmoil could turn into a global
recession was underscored by release Wednesday of an unusually
pessimistic economic forecast by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's "World Economic Outlook" said the economic turmoil
has already cost millions of jobs and more than 600 billion
dollars in lost output, which is equivalent to a country the size
of Canada shutting down for a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
