<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fed Chief Defends Hedge Fund Bailout Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Alan Greenspan, chairman of
the U.S. Federal Reserve, said Thursday the rescue of the falling
hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management (LTCM) was a rare event.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's tune was in sharp contrast with his criticism of
the Hong Kong financial authority's protective move to step in the
market not long ago.
</P>
<P>
However, he suggested the central bank would not always step in
to help investors.
</P>
<P>
Defending the rescue before the U.S. House of Representatives
Banking Committee Thursday, Greenspan said it only occurred because
of potential market disruptions and because LTCM's failure could
have hurt the world economy.
</P>
<P>
"It should... be viewed as a rare occasion, warranted because
of the potential for serious disruptions to markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The efforts last week were limited to facilitating a
private-sector agreement and had no implications for Federal
Reserve resources or policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The New York Federal Reserve last week arranged a 3.6 billion
U.S. dollar private-sector bailout of the ailing Greenwich,
Connecticut-based fund, involving 14 of the world's top commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has been criticized for allowing the hedge fund to get
so close to the brink of bankruptcy and also for organizing the
rescue of an investment vehicle for rich individuals, which some
see as encouraging others to make more risky market bets.
</P>
<P>
But New York Federal Reserve President William McDonough said
simply letting the hedge fund close out its loss-making positions
would have posed "unacceptable risks" to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan emphasized that no public money had gone into the
LTCM rescue. "This agreement was not a government bailout, in that
Federal Reserve funds were neither provided nor ever even
suggested," he said.
</P>
<P>
The failure of the huge hedge fund would have risked a "severe
drying up" of liquidity, Greenspan said, adding the already
volatile situation in world markets required a swift resolution of
the fund's troubles.
</P>
<P>
"Had the failure of LTCM triggered the seizing up of markets,
substantial damage could have been inflicted on many market
participants, including some not directly involved with the firm,
and could have potentially impaired the economies of many nations
including our own," Greenspan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
