<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Creates Defense Threat Reduction Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
established a new agency to counter nuclear, biological and
chemical weapons, Merging several Cold War agencies into one to
deal with what the Pentagon called a new world threat.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Threat Reduction Agency (DTRA) combines the
functions of other agencies born of the struggle against the
former Soviet Union which handled nuclear weapons, monitoring arms
control agreements and protecting military technology.
</P>
<P>
"It's a much more complicated world, and we're seeing the
spread of technologies falling into the hands of rogue states, of
organizations -- terrorist organizations," Deputy Defense
Secretary John Hamre told the employees of the new agency on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We're seeing the proliferation of missiles and chemical
weapons and things of this nature that...will largely characterize
the security challenge that the United States will face for
certainly the next decade and probably well beyond," Hamre said at
the agency's headquarters near Dulles International Airport in
Virginia, outside Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
The job of the new agency will be to "find ways to mitigate the
spread of dangerous technologies, find ways to contain the
proliferation of weapons to other countries, find ways to lower
the threat to the United States and to our allies," he added.
</P>
<P>
The new agency will be made up primarily of agencies founded to
reduce the threat posted by the Soviet Union before its collapse
in 1991. They include the On-Site Inspection Agency (OSIA), the
Defense Special Weapons Agency and the Defense Technical Security
Agency (DTSA).
</P>
<P>
The OSIA conducts arms control inspections and aerial
monitoring abroad; the Defense Special Weapons Agency deals with
nuclear deterrence and stockpile maintenance as well as well as
developing biological, chemical, nuclear and radiological weapons;
and the DTSA monitors export license applications and provides on
site observers for foreign launches of U.S. satellites to make
certain that unauthorized technology transfers do not occur.
</P>
<P>
A new element in the new agency will be a "force protection"
group, prompted by the fatal bombing of the Air Force's Khobar
Towers living facility in Saudi Arabia. The new group will
specialize in inspecting military sites and planning for better
security against terrorist bombings, the Washington Post said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The director of the new agency will be Jay C. Davis, a nuclear
physicist who is a former associate director of the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, the Post said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Help African Countries Tackle Debt Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain announced Friday that it
would give 30 million pounds (about 51.3 million U.S. dollars) to
help Africa's poorest nations pay off their debts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ruling Labor Party conference in Blackpool,
British International Development Secretary Clare Short said the
cash would go straight to the African Development Bank, which will
use it to help some of the poorest countries on the continent join
an accelerated debt relief program.
</P>
<P>
Short expressed her hope that all 22 poor, highly indebted
African countries will be on track for debt relief by the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
"But for Africa there is a major obstacle. The African
Development Bank cannot afford to write off its share of the debt
and this could block progress in reduing their debt burden," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Short made it clear that the greatest task was to mobilise
international political will to meet poverty eradication targets
and Britain is trying to encourage other countries to follow suit
by providing this aid package.
</P>
<P>
The program, which Britain wants to jump-start, is the Highly
Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative, envisaging speedy debt
write-offs for some of the world's poorest countries once they
have established a track record of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
This program was launched two years ago under the umbrella of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, but only
Uganda has so far secured debt relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
