<HEADLINE> Tandem Two Plan Ride into Record Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Two cyclists are to take a swipe
at a long-standing record with their attempt to race further on a
tandem in one hour than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
And if they fail in their attempt, one of the record-holders
who set the standard some 61 years ago says he will step in and
find a new partner to have another go at the record.
</P>
<P>
Karl Williamson and Adam Hardy from Yorkshire - who are making
their attempt at the Manchester Velodrome - will have to beat a
record set in Italy in 1937.
</P>
<P>
At championships in Milan, two British cyclists - Bill Paul
and Ernie Mills - rode their tandem 31 miles and 110 yards in an
hour.
</P>
<P>
Of the current record, Williamson said: "It made the
four-minute mile look like a stroll in the park."
</P>
<P>
One of the record-holders, 88-year-old Paul, is still cycling.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not understand why the record he and his late
partner set so many years ago in Milan is still standing.
</P>
<P>
But Paul is confident that the two will enter the record books
with this latest attempt.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't, then I'll find another partner and go again
myself," Paul added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
