<HEADLINE> NATO May Strike on Serbia Without U.N. Authorization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's ambassador to the
United Nations Jeremy Greenstock Friday suggested on the BBC that
NATO might initiate air strikes against Serbia even without the
authorization from the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Thursday condemned massacres of some 30
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and demanded "full and immediate
compliance" by Yugoslav leadership with a U.N. resolution that
calls for an immediate end to attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
"It looks as though (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic
will only understand the use of force or the threat of the use of
force. That is what we are now preparing. If it's necessary,
we'll use it," Greenstock said.
</P>
<P>
On whether NATO countries were prepared to act alone if they
did not receive full political backing, Greenstock said: "NATO and
the U.N. Security Council have so far gone along this route in
unity. We would like to retain that unity. If unity is not
possible, then we'll have to make our own decisions according to
the circumstances."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Defense Secretary George Robertson Friday
reaffirmed Britain's determination to use force by saying: "The
clock is ticking for Milosevic."
</P>
<P>
"He now knows that unless he complies, NATO forces, which have
been planning for some time now, are able and willing to do
something about non-compliance," he told Sky Television. 
