<HEADLINE> Drug Education Introduced into Nigerian Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The government has introduced
drug education into the curriculum of Nigeria's schools and took
the anti-drug war to the higher learning institutions as a part
of the war against drug abuse and trafficking in the country.
</P>
<P>
Musa Bamaiyi, Chairman of the National Drug Law Enforcement
Agency (NDLEA), said in capital Abuja Wednesday that the move
would make the anti-drug policy a part of the educational systems
in Nigeria, according to a Daily Times report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Launching the Obafemi Awolowo University Chapter of the
Nigerian Students Anti-drug Movement, Bamaiyi said that the
anti-drug policy had been developed to enhance a comprehensive
preventive drug education curriculum.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued last June by the African Council of
Narcotics expressed concern over the alarming increase of drug
trade in west Africa, especially in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
West African drug traffickers transship cocaine from South
America and heroin from Asia to the United states, Canada and
European countries through west African states, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
West African countries including Nigeria have become transit
centers of drug trafficking and drug abuse areas.
</P>
<P>
The statement attributed the growing drug abuse and
trafficking in the sub-region to the poor control of the vast
land, air and water ways, and lack of anti-drug education.
</P>
</TEXT>
