<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Central Bank Denies Banning Dollar Circulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Central Bank on Friday
denied suggestions of banning the circulation of hard currencies
in the country, but "the dollar should not be a payment instrument
in Russia."
</P>
<P>
Viktor Gerashchenko, chairman of the Central Bank of Russia,
addressing lawmakers at the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, criticized "those who have made suggestions, offered
suppositions and some crazy ideas over the past several days"
about an alleged ban on the dollar circulation.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized suggestions of a gold ruble, which means the
amount of ruble in circulation would be pegged to the country's
gold reserves rather than the hard currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
Gerashchenko told reporters that the gold ruble had not played
an active role in the development of the national economy in the
1920s, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The latest flurry of reports of a government plan to ban or
restrict the flow of dollars came Thursday, when the Kommersant
Daily ran the text of a document drafted by First Deputy Prime
Minister Yuri Maslyukov.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the document suggested the government was
considering harsh measures to take control of foreign currency,
putting it under the purview of the central bank and making it
difficult for banks and people to exchange and transfer hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
The report triggered panic among in the country where billions
of dollars were held by Russian citizens and businesses who do
not trust the ruble.
</P>
<P>
The national currency, which now stands at 16 rubles to the
U.S. dollar, a drop of some 61 percent from 6.3 rubles to the
dollar in mid-August, when the government of Sergei Kiriyenko
effectively devalued it.
</P>
<P>
Late Friday, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov issued a denial,
saying Maslyukov's report was "one of six options being waved
about right now."
</P>
<P>
The government still had no program for dealing with the
country's worst economic crisis since 1991.
</P>
<P>
"I should like to repeat," he said, "there is no program
of any kind." 
</P>
</TEXT>
