<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Opposition Leads the Ruling Parties in Latest Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia's key opinion poll
Newspoll, which is showing a late swing to the Labor Party,
suggests the opposition party could defeat Prime Minister John
Howard's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Sol Lebovic, leading expert with Newspoll, did not disclose
figures for the poll, to be published Saturday, but said it would
suggest the opposition Labor Party could defeat the Howard
government.
</P>
<P>
Newspoll, conducted exclusively for the nation's largest
newspaper The Australian owned by media baron Rupert Murdoch, has
a good record of predicting the 1996 election results.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the poll will show Labor leading the coalition
on primary votes by 44 percent to 40 percent, state-owned
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported Friday night
in its 7:30 television program.
</P>
<P>
"In The Weekend Australian tomorrow, we will actually show
there has been a swing back to Labor and that swing back to Labor
will get them very close to winning government if it's repeated in
tomorrow's election," Lebovic told the ABC.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we can't call it from that poll, it was conducted
during the week and as we know on election day we can get very
different trends sometimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the respected Newspoll put the ruling
coalition one point ahead of the opposition on primary votes,
although behind the opposition by 51 percent to 49 percent on a
two-party preferred basis.
</P>
<P>
This week two other polls, the Morgan and Bulletin polls, put
the Labor Party one point ahead of the coalition after
preferences, while the A.C. Nielsen poll had them all square at
50-50.
</P>
<P>
But an analysis of the four major opinion poll results shows
that the Howard government finished the election campaign slightly
ahead of the opposition Labor Party after a final week drop in
support for the opposition, the Australian Associated Press said
Friday,
</P>
<P>
An average of the four polls puts the coalition ahead on
primary votes by just over one point, 41.4 to 40.1.
</P>
<P>
While the margin is small, it's a big turnaround on last week
when Labor led by an average of 1.7 points.
</P>
<P>
However, the wire service stressed that Labor could still win
the election because it retains a narrow lead over the government
after distribution of preference votes.
</P>
<P>
Under the nation's preferential voting system, voters are
required to rank candidates in order of preference on the ballot
papers. To be elected, a candidate must achieve an absolute
majority, that is at least 50 percent plus one vote, either on
first preference or following distribution of preference votes.
</P>
<P>
If no candidate has more than half of the votes, the candidate
with the fewest votes is excluded.
</P>
<P>
This process of excluding candidates one by one continues until
one candidate has more than half the total votes and is declared
elected.
</P>
<P>
A party or coalition must hold at least 75 of the 148 seats in
the House of the Representatives to win the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
