<HEADLINE> Major News Items in U.S. Leading Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in Leading U.S. newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- NATO will have both the political authorization from its
members and the military forces in place to act against President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia in two weeks, senior American
officials said, if he does not stop the violence against ethnic
Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin said the United
States would press for "a new openness in international finance"
that would require private financial institutions to disclose more
data about their loans abroad and force private investors to pay
their share of the cost of bailing out troubled nations.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Thursday night turned back a 13.4 billion U.S.
dollar spending bill, revealing deep splits inside the Republican
majority and crushing GOP leadership hopes of sending President
Bill Clinton a series of appropriations bills in orderly fashion
before Congress is scheduled to adjourn at the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon has merged several Cold War agencies into a new
1.9 billion dollar per year Defense Threat Reduction Agency to
address growing proliferation problems and meet the threat from
weapons of mass destruction in the hands of terrorists and rogue
nations.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Russia's new government weighed a Soviet-style economic plan
drafted by the Communist economic chief, calling for currency
controls but failing to address the fiscal crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Judiciary Panel Democrats worked to limit the
scope of an impeachment inquiry to the Lewinsky scandal and keep
it from stretching into next year. 
</P>
