<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef Ebedi
stressed that Egypt is not in need of any financial aid from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the coming period.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement before leaving Thursday for New York to
attend the annual IMF meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation to the IMF meeting will seek to get
European expertise necessary for developing the country's economic
and investment potential, and meet with representatives of
international investment companies to expand foreign investment
vistas in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili
said a number of important trade agreements will be signed within
the upcoming months with some countries including the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The agreement could help solve all problems pertaining to the
trade and Egyptian exports to the U.S. market, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will also promote American investments in Egypt, he added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A symposium on privatization of banks and insurance
companies Thursday stressed the importance of Central Bank of
Egypt's role in the banking system in the light of privatization.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, organized by Egyptian Trade Union Federation,
recommended selling 10 percent of shares of banks and companies to
the workers under privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The symposium called for swiftly issuing the unified labor bill.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- TMA, Lebanon's leading cargo shipment company, will
offer a 50 percent discount for its clients during the country's
annual shopping festival due in February, 1999, the Daily Star
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The offer was announced by the company's Chairman Fadi Saab
following a meeting with Lebanese Economy and Trade Minister
Yassin Jaber.
</P>
<P>
The minister is reviewing ways with the country's businessmen
to make sure the coming festival successful through a sharp
reduction of goods price.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A large British economic delegation is expected to
visit Lebanon on October 6 to discuss opening market opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The trade delegation, representing 11 companies from different
sectors of industry, will also visit Syria and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The head of the Beirut Chamber of Commerce and
Industry Adnan Kassar has been elected president of the 130-member
International Chamber of Commerce (ICC), press reports said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Beirut-based Middle East Reporter newsletter said that
Kassar is the first Lebanese to be chosen as ICC president, who
works to uphold the principles of market economy, free trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
Kassar, a banker and also president of the Arab Chambers of
Commerce, will take over the two-year post in January, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
