<HEADLINE> Squall Lashes Indian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A squall with a wind spead of
80 kilometers per hour lashed New Delhi Friday, bringing down the
temperature, disrupting power supply and uprooting trees, electric
and telephone poles in many areas of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Dark clouds enveloped the sky around 10:40 this morning
followed by thunder and heavy downpour around lunch time.
</P>
<P>
Uprooted hoardings, television antennas and trees hindered
smooth flow of traffic in some areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
The mercury dipped by 10 degrees Celsius from 31 degrees to 21
degrees following the squall and rain.
</P>
<P>
A meteorological official here said the squall was rare for the
month of October.
</P>
<P>
The squall from the north-westerly direction was under the
combined influence of cyclonic circulation over north Rajasthan
and neighboring states and a low cyclonic circulation over the
south, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
