<HEADLINE> Taliban Envoy: Iranian Planes Violate Afghan Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian jet fighters and
helicopters on Friday twice violated Afghanistan's airspace, the
Taliban's envoy Maulvi Saeed-ur-Rehman Haqqani said here.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani told the private News Network International (NNI) that
15 Iranian planes entered Afghanistan's airspace from Nimroz and
returned to Iran while flying over Herat province between 9:00 to
11:00 a.m. (Afghan Standard Time).
</P>
<P>
He said 15 helicopters also violated Afghanistan's airspace
between 8:30 a.m. to 10:00 a.m..
</P>
<P>
The Taliban envoy asked the United Nations Security Council to
take serious notice of the Iranian actions and warned that such
actions will have disastrous effects if not checked.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Taliban government showed patience and did not
retaliate in the light of recent Ulema fatawa (religious decree).
</P>
<P>
Tension between Iran and the Taliban regime has been high since
the murder of seven Iranian diplomats by the student militia in
northern Afghanistan early August. Iran, who has vowed to reserve
the right of taking any action to revenge, is holding grand
military games involving more than 200,000 troops along the
Iran-Afghan border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
