<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Farm Output to Rise One-tenth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's total
agricultural production is expected to register a 10 percent
increase in the current 1998/99 agricultural year over the
previous 1997/98, an Ethiopian minister has said.
</P>
<P>
A local report Friday quoted Minister of Economic Development
and Cooperation Girma Birru as saying that Ethiopia's total
agricultural production which has suffered an overall drop of 7.6
percent in 1997/98, will register a rise of 10 percent in
1998/99.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, apart from favorable weather
conditions, the government's intensified efforts to expand its
agricultural extension package program across the country also
contribute to the growth.
</P>
<P>
Other factors that are expected to boost farm output this year
include improved agricultural practices, adequate supplies of
fertilizer and selected seed and provision of rural credit, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's major farm crops are teff, barley, maize, wheat,
sorghum, horsebeans, chickpeas, lentils, vetch, neug and linseed.
Other important agricultural products include coffee, livestock
and dairy products, fruits and vegetables and spices.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture in Ethiopia accounts for 50 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP), 90 percent of the country's total export
earnings and 85 percent of total employment.
</P>
<P>
Hence, agriculture forms the core of the Ethiopian
government's development strategy which aims to increase the
productivity of small holder agriculture, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural extension package program, major ingredient
of the government's development strategy, which in the past years
was confined to only food grains, is expanded in 1998/99 to
incorporate animal breeding, soil and water conservation, forest
development and irrigation, according to the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
