<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to First Restore Domestic Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) will
first restore its domestic flights after resuming operations on
October 7, the airlines said here Friday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
PAL will resume operations on Wednesday (October 7) following
the favorable outcome of the two-day referendum among ground
employees belonging to the PAL Employees Association.
</P>
<P>
"Initially, PAL will restore flights to 14 domestic
destinations out of Manila. The flag carrier will utilize 9
aircraft. Resumption of international service is now being
reviewed," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Before the closure at midnight September 23, PAL served 16
domestic points and flew dozens of international routes.
</P>
<P>
"Bookings will be accepted beginning Saturday (October 3) in
all PAL reservation and ticket offices," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
During the referendum, 3,247 people, or 61 percent of the total
voters, voted for a new deal brokered by President Joseph Estrada
between the management and labor union officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, the labor union will suspend its
collective bargaining agreement for 10 years. In exchange, the
management will give employees 20 percent of the PAL ownership and
three seats in the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
PAL, the oldest airlines in Asia, closed shop due to heavy
losses and the breakdown of talks between the management and the
labor union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
