<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Better Ties with Hezbollah's Spiritual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of Iran's
supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei are on a secret visit to
Lebanon to improve relations with Sheikh Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, spiritual leader of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
A source close to Hezbollah, or Party of God, told Xinhua
Friday that the Iranian delegation, led by Hojateslam Hijazi, also
aims to improve Fadlallah's ties with Hezbollah's leadership.
</P>
<P>
The cleric's relation with Iran started to sour especially
after the death of one of the grand religious leaders of the
Shiite Muslims, Al-Sayed Abu Al-Kasem Al-Khoui, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Fadlallah's assertion of his authority as spiritual leader of
the Shiites and his unconventional teaching methods were not
welcomed by some religious and political figures in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Several Iranian scholars published books contesting Fadlallah's
religious and historical theories.
</P>
<P>
The source, who asked not to be named, said Iran wanted to
improve its relations with the Shiite cleric by way of extending
him an invitation to visit Tehran, as Fadlallah has been to the
country for eight years.
</P>
<P>
But Fadlallah had said that he would visit Iran provided he
was granted an exclusive meeting with Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the cleric has on more than one occasion voiced his
objection to the idea of combining religious and political
authorities in one person within Hezbollah, which is currently led
by Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, established in the wake of Israel's second invasion
of Lebanon in 1982, is leading a guerrilla war, allegedly with
Iranian financial backing, to oust about 1,500 Israeli soldiers
out of the occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 after two invasions with the claimed aim to protect its
north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila Advised to Talk to Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Uganda still wants Congolese
(K) President Laurent Kabila to talk directly with the Tutsi-led
rebels fighting to oust him, a Ugandan senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, the minister of state for regional affairs,
made the demand Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Friday's New Vision paper quoted the minister as saying that
Uganda has never changed this demand of direct talks between
Kabila and "other political forces like Tshisekedi in Congo."
</P>
<P>
Since the eruption of the rebellion in eastern town of Goma in
early August, Kabila and his allies represented by President
Robert Mugabe have rejected any kind of direct talks with rebels
who control a large area including major cities and towns in
eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan minister had just returned home from a meeting
with Mugabe to whom he conveyed a message from Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
With more African countries being involved in the conflict,
Museveni is seeking more chances to exchange ideas with foreign
leaders on the issue.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Friday morning by the Presient's Office
said Museveni has just returned from Libya where he held talks
with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and presidents of Eritrea,
Chad and Niger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
