<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief Observer Reaffirms Cambodia's Election Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Sven G. Linder, chief
observer of the Joint International Observer Group (JIOG) in
Cambodia, reiterated Friday that Cambodia's election on July 26
was "free and fair" with no major irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Linder said in his final statement released on Friday that "the
opening, in Siem Reap on September 24, of the new National
Assembly marked the formal end of the election period in Cambodia
1998."
</P>
<P>
"I am still as convinced as I was then that the assessment we
made at that time, also similar to that of the trained and serious
national observers, was correct," he stated.
</P>
<P>
"During its continued work, the EU Observation Unit has found
no indication of flaws and frauds of a magnitude that could have
distorted the will of the Cambodian voters as that will was
expressed on the 26th of July," Linder stressed.
</P>
<P>
Cambodians went to polls on July 26 to elect a new National
Assembly. The ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP) led by Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen won the election which was disclaimed by
some political parties as being "full of fraud". But the
international observers' assessment is that the election was "free
and fair to an extent that enabled it to reflect, in a credible
way, the will of the Cambodian people."
</P>
<P>
The JIOG received criticism from some quarters for allegedly
having issued its statement prematurely. "To me the timing we
chose was right, and even necessary," Linder insisted in his
statement.
</P>
<P>
"To me and my fellow international observers the Cambodian
people's wish for democracy was very clearly demonstrated on
polling day itself, Sunday, 26 July. The atmosphere at the many
polling stations we visited as the voters waited to cast their
ballot was calm and solemn, even festive at times."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Linder pointed out that the standard of work of the
National Election Committee and other election-related bodies in
the post-election phase has not corresponded to the generally high
standard displayed during the previous phases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
