<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians to Vote for New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 12 million
Australians are going to vote Saturday for a new government and a
new prime minister that will lead this country towards the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Vying for those 12 million votes are 1435 candidates including
about 400 female candidates, 1106 running for 148 House of
Representatives seats and 329 for 40 senate seats, while the
previous highest numbers were in 1993 when 943 candidates ran for
the House and 266 for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four parties are fielding candidates, up from 31 in
1996, plus 115 independents for the Senate and 26 for the House.
</P>
<P>
Except the main rivals, namely the Liberal and National Party
coalition and the Australian Labor Party, there are some minor
parties such as the Democrats, the Green Party and newly organized
One Nation Party. Besides, there are some still smaller parties
such as the Abolish Child Support Court Party, the Australian Bill
of Rights Group, CTA Child Protection Party, and Unity-Say No to
Hanson.
</P>
<P>
Almost 9,000 polling stations are to open around the nation
from 08:00 a.m. (22:00 Friday GMT) to 06:00 p.m. (08:00 Saturday
GMT). They are manned by 700 full-time staff and some 63,000
part-time staff.
</P>
<P>
To enable everyone to vote, the Australian Electoral Commission
(AEC) arranged over 500 mobile polling teams visiting 2,100
hospitals and nursing homes and 120 remote locations. If anyone
wants to avoid the voting without a very good excuse, he will be
fined 20 Australian dollars (12 U.S. dollars) for not voting.
</P>
<P>
While all ordinary ballot papers, about 88 percent of the total
votes, will be counted on Saturday evening, and the first results
will start appearing at the National Tally Room about 06:30 p.m.
(08:30 GMT). But the AEC must wait 13 days for postal votes to
arrive from remote areas and overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
