<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Submits New Bill on Expression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government Friday
submitted a new bill on freedom of expression to replace the
government regulation in lieu of law on freedom of expression
which was turned down by the legislative body recently.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the new bill to the House of Representatives,
Justice Minister Muladi said the bill is more regulative than
repressive, and thus accommodates the people's wish to uphold and
protect human rights.
</P>
<P>
"In society, freedom needs to be regulated to make it a
precondition for the existence of a civilized nation," Muladi
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the bill does not limit the people's freedom, let alone
ban them from expressing their aspirations.
</P>
<P>
It regulates this freedom to enable the people to convey their
aspirations in a more effective and secure manner and maintain
public order at the same time, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It does not aim to undermine the people's rights and freedom.
Similar laws are in place in other countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The new bill regulates the methods by which people could
express their views in public places, describes the role of the
police in mass actions, and states the legal penalties.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, Muladi said, every Indonesian citizen has the
right to express his or her thoughts freely and seek legal
protection.
</P>
<P>
It, however, compels every citizen to honor the rights and
freedom of other people, abide by the law, maintain public order,
and uphold national unity.
</P>
<P>
The bill also compels organizers of rallies or protest
movements to submit a written notification to the police if the
number of participants is less than 100 or obtain a permit from
the police if the number is more than 100.
</P>
<P>
The police has the right to disperse a rally or demonstration
should the participants commit any criminal offense and disturb
peace and order, Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
The House turned down the government regulation in lieu of law
on September 29. House members had questioned the limitation to 50
of the number of participants in rallies without approval and some
other aspects of the proposed regulation had also been questioned,
including the requirement for written approval and the time and
place for the expression as well as methods for dispersing such
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
