<HEADLINE> Air Quality Report for China's Major Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The China Environmental
Monitoring Center today released its latest weekly air quality
report for major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Most areas throughout China recorded sparse precipitation
between September 25 and October 1, with deteriorating air quality
in northwest and north China, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report lists the atmospheric pollution index
(API) for sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxide (NOX) and total
suspended particles (TSP).
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration reports five
levels of air quality. An API rating of 0-50 (level I) indicates
excellent air quality, 51-100 (level II) good quality, 101-200
(level III) slight pollution, 201-300 (level IV) medium pollution,
and over 300 (level V) heavy pollution.
</P>
<P>
The air quality report for September 25 to October
1 follows:
