<HEADLINE> China Donates Medicines for Nairobi Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Medical utilities and medicine
donated by the Chinese government for the victims in August 7
bomb blast arrived at the Kenyan capital here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Health Minister Jackson Kalweo expressed appreciation
at the donation ceremony, saying that China has been helpful for
this east African country for years.
</P>
<P>
"China is very friendly to Kenya and helps us in many areas,"
he said, calling for enhanced cooperation between the two
countries especially in their efforts against national
calamities.
</P>
<P>
He said Kenya and China are getting closer following Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi's three visits to China since the 1980s
and Chinese leader Jiang Zemin's Kenyan trip in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There are 117 cases of various kinds of medicines and medical
apparatuses including syringes and gloves, but this reporter
could not sound out how much they are worth.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador An Yongyu reiterated the Chinese
government's deep sympathy with and condolence to Kenyans
suffering from the August 7 bombing aimed at the U.S. embassy in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
