<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Increase Interests in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Growing international confidence
in Nigeria's march to democracy could translate into heavy
investments as they have expressed their desire to do business in
Nigeria, a senior business official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Baba Bakar Gujbawu, Chief Executive of the Nigerian
Investment Promotion Commission, said in capital Abuja Thursday
that some European and Asian countries had already pledged to
normalize economic relations with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The pledges, when fulfilled, would translate into greater
investment inflow from the countries to the Nigeria's economy, he
said, The Guardian newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Following a recent visit to the United States by Nigerian Head
of State Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, This Day newspaper said
Friday that the number of American business people seeking
Nigerian visa to visit the country has increased three times.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Ambassador to the United States Alhaji Hassan Adamu
told the paper that the White House meeting between President
Bill Clinton and Gen. Abubakar had opened the floodgate for visa
application from American businessmen wishing to do business in
the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the upsurge in the demand for Nigerian visa
followed the deliberation of the two leaders on diverse issues
like rescheduling of Nigerian debt, inflow of foreign investment
to Nigeria and lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Gen. Abubakar's meeting in New York with
American corporate groups consisting of 50 business executives
was another impetus to the new development.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Gen. Abubakar assured them of the nation's
preparedness to shed up to 40 percent government equity in the
telecommunication and energy sectors.
</P>
<P>
A leading South African oil company, Engen, is reportedly
exploring the possibility of investing in Nigeria's oil gas
sector.
</P>
<P>
Engen Chief Executive Officer Roy Angel told a correspondent
of the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) based in Johannesburg that
Engen alongside its partner, Malaysian Firm Petronas, would seek
to invest in offshore petrol and gas projects in Nigeria within
next year.
</P>
<P>
According to him, investors' confidence is gradually being
restored in Nigeria following the steps so far taken by the
Central Bank of Nigeria and the Abubakar regime to return the
country to democratic rule and for taking steps to reunite the
country with the international community.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, many western countries have banned
further investment in the West African country to protest the
poor human rights record of the late former Head of State Sani
Abacha regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Accused of Backing Rebels to Fight Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Sudan is hiding and supporting
the rebels who are fighting against the Ugandan government, a
Ugandan official said here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Sarapio Karashani, the resident district chairman of Kampala,
made the statement at a security sensitization meeting at the
Ground Show of Uganda Manufacturers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of Lord Resistance Army (LRA) "come and attack us"
and then retreat to their bases in southern Sudan, he charged.
</P>
<P>
Karashani asserted that Uganda's problem with Sudan is not
their internal affairs, but the fact that they hide and support
those who attack us.
</P>
<P>
"The person who comes to steal your television, and hijack
your children is definitely not a good neighbor," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The rebels and terrorists are reportedly targeting on big
markets, vulnerable buses and big churches for raids.
</P>
<P>
Karashani advised those present at the meeting to contribute
to the peaceful environment.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting which was attended by more than 100 local and
foreign manufacturers, security officers advised the exhibitors
to take precautions against any possible bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair is scheduled for October 6-12 and this meeting
is part of the measures taken to ensure absolute security and
success of the exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
