<HEADLINE> Exhibitors Warned of Dangers in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Exhibitors who will take part
in an international exhibition here slated for 6-12 October are
warned of the potential security dangers they may face and are
advised to take precautions against any bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting attended by more than 100 managers and
manufacturers Friday morning in the Show Ground of Uganda
Manufacturers' Association (UMA), security commanders give
specific tips to the exhibitors on how to ensure safety and act
on an emergency.
</P>
<P>
James Wulwana, the chairman of UMA, said: "we are open to
whatever happens. To ensure the success of the trade fair,
security should be seriously addressed and precautions be taken."
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Namanya, the police commander of Kampala region, told
the gathering that terrorism is an international crime and called
for community awareness against these activities.
</P>
<P>
One security officer said terrorism is a product of bad
politics and politics can't be divorced from economy and called
for those managers' commitment and contribution to security.
</P>
<P>
"We should not give room to terrorists to come and plant a
bomb. And we cannot claim responsibility enough without your
involvement. The best thing to do is to organize yourselves," he
said.
</P>
<P>
At the function, police telephone numbers are offered to those
present, hoping they can contact the nearest police station in
case of emergency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
