<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports Up by 19 Percent in 8 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The depreciation of the local
currency continued to boost Philippine exports as earnings for the
first eight months this year grew by 18.9 percent to 19.06 billion
U.S. dollars from the year-ago level of 16.03 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Data released Friday by the National Statistics Office showed
that for the month of August alone, total exports receipts
increased by 17.5 percent to reach 2.65 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and components, accounting for 51.2 percent of the
aggregate, posted a 37.2-percent increase during the month to 1.36
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The item was followed by articles and clothing apparel and
input and output peripheral units whose sales amounted to 230.33
million and 180.30 million dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Top exports for August also included coconut oil, woodcraft and
furniture and other products manufactured from materials imported
on consignment basis, according to the data.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan were the largest markets for
Philippine products in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
