<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to Re-open on October 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Philippine
Airlines (PAL) employees voted for a new deal between the
management and the labor union in a two-day referendum which ended
Friday, paving the way for the re-opening of PAL on October 7.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura Magsalin, executive director of the Labor
Department's national conciliation and mediation board, said that
3,247 yes votes, or 61 percent of the 5,324 total votes cast, and
1,794 no votes were canvassed.
</P>
<P>
"It only means PAL's re-opening on October 7," Magsalin said as
he referred to yes votes' wide winning margin over no votes cast
mostly by hard-liners inside the PAL Employees Association.
</P>
<P>
Magsalin said the referendum netted a turnout of 81.3 percent
and that, of the votes canvassed, 106 were spoiled and 177
segregated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Avelino Capili, a proponent of no votes, said that
the hard-liners will file a petition before the Supreme Court,
disputing the legality of the agreement signed by labor union
officials and the management early this week.
</P>
<P>
PAL, the oldest airlines in Asia, was shut down on September 23
due to heavy losses and the breakdown of talks between the
management and the labor union.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada brokered the new deal, according to
which the labor union will suspend its collective bargaining
agreement for 10 years. In exchange, the management will give
employees 20 percent of the PAL ownership and three seats in the
board of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
