<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide Vietnam with 580 million US Dollar Loan Per Annum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) plans to grant
Vietnam a loan worth 580 million U.S. dollars each year in the
1999-2002 period, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount of lending would depend on needs and on
progress of the policy agenda, poverty reduction and portfolio
management, the WB Vietnam country director Andrew Steer told a
news conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The WB decision was made at its Board of Executive Directors
meeting in Washington last week, which discussed the bank group's
country assistance strategy for Vietnam covering the period
1998-99 to 2001-02.
</P>
<P>
According to the WB, the International Development Association
approved 19 projects worth 2 billion dollars in Vietnam from 1994
to 1998. Over half of the lending has gone to the much-needed
upgrading of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The WB recognized Vietnam's remarkable progress over the past
years, saying that Vietnam's economic renewal process has yielded
unprecedented levels of GDP growth of eight percent per year on
average between 1990 and 1997, and an impressive reduction in the
share of the population living in acute poverty.
</P>
<P>
Despite this progress, the WB noted that Vietnam remains one of
the poorest countries in the world, with a per capita income of
only about 300 dollars per annum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
