<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Approach Cannot Resolve Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Military approach cannot resolve
the crisis in the Great Lakes region, the visiting special envoy
of the European Union (EU) said in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
EU envoy for the Great Lakes region Aldo Ajello said this
during his meeting with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After their meeting, Ajello told reporters that "it will not
be easy to resolve the crisis in Congo (Kinshasa) because many
interests are involved in this conflict."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the crisis in the Great Lakes region, the EU envoy
pointed out that people should give up their illusion that "the
military approach can solve the political problems."
</P>
<P>
The national Noticias newspaper Friday quoted Ajello as saying
that he had come to "know what President Chissano thinks about
the crisis in the Great Lakes."
</P>
<P>
"Mozambique is a successful model for peace process," the EU
envoy said, adding that "I am confident that its role will be
helpful to the entire Great Lakes region."
</P>
<P>
Ajello acknowledged that the difficulties facing the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) include the participation of
all political parties in the democratization, the establishment
of a government of national unity and reconciliation and the
preparation for elections.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there is a problem concerning the Tutsi Banyamulenge
who are attempting to topple the government led by DRC President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the border disputes between the DRC and its
neighbors, Uganda, Brundi and Rwanda, also have their influences
in the peace and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
"It should be made clear to all the countries concerned in
this region that the crisis must be resolved in a political way,"
Ajello noted. "A political resolution can never be reached unless
their individual interests are taken into consideration."
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy arrived in Maputo Wednesday after his visit to
South Africa. He also held talks with Mozambican Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Ajello who had been the special representative of the United
Nations Secretary-General to Mozambique for the peace process in
the southern African country from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to leave Maputo for Namibia Friday before
going to Zambia, Angola, Rwanda and Tanzania to mediate for peace
in the Great Lakes region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
