<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Record Growth Next Year: Bank Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will record
positive economic growth next year after registering negative
growth this year, Bank Negara (State Bank) Governor Ali Abul
Hassan Sulaiman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minus 4.8 percent gross domestic product growth in the
first half of this year would mean that 1998 would see an overall
negative growth rate, he told a briefing here without giving exact
figures.
</P>
<P>
The governor said he could not provide exact numbers for the
time being as they were changing for the better each time
following the implementation of various financial and economic
measures adopted by the government.
</P>
<P>
More definite figures will emerge when the 1999 Budget is
presented on October 23, he said, adding he was confident that the
local economy would see a dramatic turnaround following the
adoption of the measures which included effecting greater
liquidity in the banking system, greater access to lending and
lower interest rates for loans.
</P>
<P>
He said signs of an economic recovery were already there and
there were already several "feel good" factors as far as economic
recovery in the country was concerned.
</P>
<P>
On the imposition of selective exchange controls from last
month, Ali said the Malaysian government had to act fast and
decisively to protect its economy, with a main objective to regain
monetary independence to enable the country to introduce measures
based solely on domestic conditions.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy registered a negative growth of 1.8 percent,
which was revised to negative 2.8 percent later for the first
quarter and saw a negative growth of 6.8 percent for the second
quarter this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
