<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Lowers Insurers' Capital, Solvency Margins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday announced
some new measures to help the insurance industry tide over the
economic downturn, including lowering the capital and solvency
margin requirements of insurers.
</P>
<P>
The minimum capital requirement for direct insurers will be
reduced to 35 million ringgit (about 9.21 million U.S. dollars)
from 50 million ringgit (about 13.157 million U.S. dollars) by
December 31 this year and the minimum margin of solvency for each
class of business to 30 million ringgit (about 7.894 million U.S.
dollars) from 50 million ringgit (about 13.157 million U.S.
dollars) from January 1,1999, Bank Negara (State Bank) Governor
Ali Abul Hassan Sulaiman announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The insurance industry has shown signs of a slowdown and has to
be revitalized after recording only a marginal increase in
combined premium income of 3.4 percent for the first half of this
year, compared with 19.3 percent in the same period last year,
Ali, who is also director-general of insurance, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The capital and solvency margin requirements, under the
Insurance Act 1996, were introduced early last year to gear
insurers to be larger players and to prepare them to compete in a
liberalized environment.
</P>
<P>
Ali said asset growth of the industry had also slowed down to
6.5 percent, during the first half of this year, from 11.1 percent
in the first half of 1997, largely due to deflation in asset
values as well as contraction in business.
</P>
<P>
Other measures announced include allowing insurers to maintain
a minimum of 70 percent in aggregate of the insurance fund
liabilities and margin of solvency in the form of admitted assets.
</P>
<P>
The balance 30 percent of the liabilities and margin of
solvency could be supported by other assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
