<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Earnings Likely to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports are likely to
earn 53.6 billion U.S. dollars this year, down by 8 percent from
last year, the Board of Investment said in a statement available
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The board based its prediction on trade figures for January to
August, which showed export returns of 35.98 billion dollars, down
5.4 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of cars, pickups and motorcycles were promising in the
first half. Exports for the year would likely reach 58,000
vehicles and 200,000 motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Several projects backed by government promotions maintained
their export potential, including canned tuna, frozen fish, frozen
chicken, rubber gloves, tyres, canned pineapples, jewelry, toys,
shoes and leather.
</P>
<P>
But in terms of export value, they were unlikely to show better
returns in the second half of the year than the first half.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural exports declined by 10 percent in the first seven
months, processed farm products by 3 percent and industrial goods
by 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports in January to August had contracted by 37 percent to
28.516 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In August alone, imports declined by 33.2 percent to 3.391
billion dollars from 12 months earlier. Imports for the year would
likely total 42.1 billion dollars, a drop of 33.5 percent from
last year's level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-election Jitters Cause Australian Dollar to End Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Pre-election jitters finally
caught up with the Australian dollar Friday and caused it to close
slightly weaker.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 59.37 U.S. cents from
Thursday's close of 59.39 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
On the day the local currency traded in a range of more than
three quarters of a U.S. cent, touching a high of 59.90 U.S. cents
and falling to a low of 59.09 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Nick Volanakis, foreign exchange dealer with Colonial State
Bank, said election jitters, particularly concerning the fact the
campaign is close, are affecting the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
More than 12 million Australians go to the polls Saturday for
an election which has been fought largely on the issue of tax
reform.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said the first fear among markets is that the
election might result in a hung parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The second fear might be that the ruling Liberal Party gets in
but with a very small majority which makes it hard to govern,
particularly with all the legislation they have to get through,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The expected close result is guaranteed to keep the markets
range trading until a definitive outcome emerges.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading in Sydney the local currency was buying
80.04 Japanese yen from 81.21 yen and 0.9807 German marks from
0.9913 yen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
