<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, October 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Thursday the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was ready for military strikes
against Serbian forces in Kosovo, but hoped the crisis would be
resolved through diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"The combined threat of the use of force and diplomacy is the
best way of proceeding," Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said after key national security officials briefed most of the
Senate on the situation in Kosovo. (US-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia lodged a strong protest against Albania
on Thursday for the killing of five of its border guards by armed
men coming from the Albanian territory.
</P>
<P>
The official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug quoted a note of
protest as saying that the incident was a gross violation of
Yugoslav territory. (Yugoslavia-Albania-Protest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Slovak Foreign Minister Zdenka Kramplova resigned
Wednesday following the defeat of the ruling Movement for a
Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) in the country's legislative elections
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Thursday said that Kramplova's
resignation had been accepted by National Assembly Chairman Ivan
Gashparovic who was acting on behalf of the president partly.
</P>
<P>
Krapmlova, 40, became the Slovak foreign minister on June,
1997. (Slovak Republic-FM-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Democrats in the U.S House of Representatives are
drafting a proposal for a brief impeachment inquiry restricted to
President Bill Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky, officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Several officials said the Democratic proposal, designed as an
alternative to the open-ended inquiry envisioned by Republicans,
may refer to censure as an eventual resolution of the case against
Clinton, but this would come into play only after a formal
investigation, according to an Associated Press report.
(US-Democrats-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn
Thursday called for "close coordination on economic policies
between Europe and the United States."
</P>
<P>
The minister made the statement prior to a meeting in
Washington Saturday of finance ministers and central bank
governors of the Group of 7 countries. (France-Europe-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Thursday it was
disappointed that Cuba told U.N. World Food Program that it would
not accept an American contribution to the program's appeal for
emergency food donations for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
After the World Food Program launched the appeal several weeks
ago in response to a severe drought in eastern Cuba, the United
States informed it that it would consider contributing up to
one-third of the amount of food requested. (US-Cuba) 
</P>
</TEXT>
