<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Takes Program for Post-Flood Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken a massive program of 42.43 billion taka (902.8 million U.S.
dollars) for reconstructing the damaged infrastructure and
rehabilitating the people distressed by this century's worst
floods in the country, an English newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has recently directed the
concerned ministries to start open market sale of rice,
distribution of vulnerable group feeding (VGF) and vulnerable
group development cards to reduce the sufferings of the people in
the flood-hit areas, The Bangladesh Observer said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina has also asked the ministries to start the test relief
and food for work program in the rural areas from October to
generate employment.
</P>
<P>
The government has received a demand for 22.96 billion taka
(488.5 million dollars) on the emergency basis from 16 concerned
ministries for the infrastructure reconstruction damaged by the
flood. The ministries also prepared projects worth 19.72 billion
taka (419.6 million dollars) for immediate implementation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has started distribution of 32.7
billion taka (695.7 million dollars) as agricultural credit among
the farmers to rehabilitate the agriculture sector and raise food
production to offset the deficit due to crop failure during the
floods.
</P>
<P>
In view of the sufferings of the flood victims, the government
has already issued 1,075,370 VGF cards which will provide 16
kilograms of foodgrains per month to each family under an extended
VGF program. The government will issue 2.5 million VGF cards for
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Over two-thirds of the country were hit by the two-month-long
floods which left a trail of devastation in 52 out of the 64
districts with more than 30 million people seriously affected and
total losses preliminarily estimated at 3.4 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
