<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gets 209 Mln Dollars in Flood Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh had already received
commitments of 209.77 million U.S. dollars in cash and kind as
flood aid from donor countries and agencies by September 30, media
reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Of the pledged amount, 141.05 million dollars are in food aid,
58.57 million dollars in cash and 10.15 million dollars in kind,
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said Thursday on his return from
New York where he attended the 53rd United Nations General
Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
Azad said 27 countries had pledged their full support to the
Bangladeshi government's efforts in overcoming the impact of
floods and launching the post-flood rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
He had separate meetings with foreign ministers of as many as
17 countries on the sidelines of the U.N. session, during which he
reiterated the appeal for immediate assistance for flood victims
and the need for intensive post-flood reconstruction and
rehabilitation works.
</P>
<P>
As the flood situation was deteriorating further, the
Bangladeshi government on August 24 decided to issue an
international appeal for 789 million U.S. dollars in aid to fund
relief and post-flood rehabilitation programs. It then directed
the country's diplomatic missions abroad and sent high-ranking
officials to seek assistance from donor countries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The worst-ever flooding in a century in this South Asian
country had gripped as much as two-thirds of the country for 10
weeks and affected about half of its 127 million people. The
floods left more than 1,100 people dead and caused an estimated
loss of 3.4 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
