<HEADLINE> Talks between Lesotho Government, Oppositions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the
Lesotho government and opposition party alliance met Friday
morning in capital Maseru for talks aimed at breaking the
country's current political impasse.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by South African Safety and Security
Minister Sydney Mufamadi, began just after 9:00 a.m., South
African Press Association quoted informed sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the parties in the mountain
kingdom talked face-to-face since the political turmoil started
two months ago amid allegations of fraud in the May 23 election.
</P>
<P>
"At last we meet the government face to face and hope that the
outcome will be good to the nation," opposition alliance
spokeswoman Mamelo Morrison told mass media just before the talks
began at the United Nations House in Maseru.
</P>
<P>
The multiparty talks are aimed at settling the controversy
over allegations that Lesotho's May 23 general election was
rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy
(LCD).
</P>
<P>
Paks Mankahlana, aide to President Nelson Mandela, said the
South Africans were optimistic that progress would be made in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition Basotho National Party leader Retsilisitsoe
Sekhonyane Thursday urged all parties in the country to trust
each other and to negotiate in good faith.
</P>
<P>
"Compromise is the language of negotiation," local daily the
Star Friday quoted Sekhonyane saying. But he declined to specify
issues the opposition was prepared to compromise on.
</P>
<P>
He said the opposition was still insisting that the government
led by Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili resign, and on the
formation of an interim government of national unity, before
fresh election is held.
</P>
<P>
The ruling LCD could not be reached for comment on Friday
morning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
