<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Kim Beazley: Sharp, Decent Opposition Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Kim Beazley, leader of
Australia's opposition Labor Party, does not bid for the prime
ministership as a man who believes he was destined to lead the
nation.
</P>
<P>
A strong sense of duty rather than the fierce fire of ambition
has fuelled his political ascent during the past few years.
</P>
<P>
If Beazley wins Saturday's election, he will be the first
Australian opposition leader to oust a government after only one
term since the Great Depression in the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Whether he will win this election or not, Beazley, 49, has
demonstrated his strengths and capability by being neck-and-neck
with Prime Minister John Howard in the opinion polls in final
three weeks before the October 3 polling day.
</P>
<P>
He was unanimously elected leader of the Labor Party in March,
1996, and succeeded in avoiding the ugly post-election
bloodletting and disunity that many had presumed would be
inevitable in the aftermath of a crushing 1996 electoral defeat
under the leadership of Paul Keating.
</P>
<P>
"I was pleased and unexpectedly (elected) Labor leader and when
I got the job I did not expect to be prime minister," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
But he changed his mind after he was angered by Howard's
"encouragement" of Pauline Hanson divisiveness, and the
government's nursing home policy, which was so unpopular among the
old Australians that the Howard government had to back down last
year.
</P>
<P>
"The combination of the two caused me to think this government
was not fit to govern," Beazley said.
</P>
<P>
A sharp, decent person, Beazley is a politician liked and
admired by both sides of the politics. He served as minister for
13 years in the Bob Hawke and subsequent Paul Keating government.
</P>
<P>
Despite being an ardent supporter of Hawke, who was challenged
and defeated by his treasurer Keating in the 1990 election,
Beazley was trusted and promoted to finance minister and later
deputy prime minister by Keating.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, John Howard, who was then in opposition, said if
he had to form a national government in a time of crisis, Beazley
was one of two persons he would select from the Labor Party, the
arch-rival of Howard's Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
Beazley became the youngest ever Australian Defense Minister in
1984 at the age of 35. For more than five years, Beazley turned
the country's defensive structure upside down, dragging it into
the modern era by spending several billion dollars on new
frigates, submarines, helicopters.
</P>
<P>
During the election campaign, Beazley said he wants to be
remembered as an education prime minister of Australia if he wins
the election, and outlined his vision for the future Australia as
a country where "Australians are skilled, secure, confident and
united people."
</P>
<P>
"I want an Australia where no one turns on fellow Australians,
but recognized in our great multicultural and multiracial
society," he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his election campaign, Beazley listed unemployment as
the top priority issue he would tackle if elected, and offered
more benefit to the Australian middle and low income earners in
his tax package than what Howard's tax plan did.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1948, Beazley was educated at Oxford University, where
he befriended Tony Blair, now the British prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He has three children, and is married to Susie Annus, an
immigrant from Hungary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: John Howard: a Social Conservative, Economic Liberal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Saturday's federal election
will decide the status of John Howard in Australia's history:
either a tenacious politician that will usher Australia into the
21st century with a new taxation system, or the first
one-term-only Australian prime minister since the Great Depression
in the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Howard, 58, has risen, despite all sorts of impediments and
obstacles in the past 24 years, to the highest office in Australia
after he unseated his predecessor Paul Keating in 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
By the time he became a federal MP in 1974, Howard, a lawyer by
training, already had 18 years of politics behind him. The next
year he was made Minister for Business and Consumer Affairs in
Malcolm Fraser's government, then Minister Assisting The Prime
Minister in 1977, Minister for Special Trade Negotiations, and
Treasurer until 1983.
</P>
<P>
He had first challenged for the leadership of the Liberal Party
of Australia in 1983, the first of the party's consecutive 13
years in opposition, but lost to Andrew Peacock. Two years later,
Howard seized the leadership.
</P>
<P>
As leader of the opposition, Howard said in 1988 that the rate
of Asian immigration should be slowed, which he later repeatedly
regretted. A year later, He lost the leadership to Peacock.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Peacock and his handpicked successor John
Hewson as leader of their party over their 1990 and 1993 federal
electoral defeats and their departure from Australia's political
arena paved the way for Howard's return to the top job of the
party.
</P>
<P>
Howard's battle first failed and Alexander Downer was made
leader of the party, but the young leader's repeated mistakes cost
him leadership in 1995 and Howard finally recaptured the position.
</P>
<P>
Australian voters' weariness of the 13 years of rule by the
Australian Labor Party and their yearnings for a change of
government led to a landslide victory of Howard's Liberal Party
and National Party coalition in 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
He was short, bespectacled and hard of hearing, but his
tenacity and good luck enabled him to become the 25th person to
occupy the office of Prime Minister of Australia, and the only
Liberal Party heavyweight to survive the party's 13 consecutive
years in opposition.
</P>
<P>
"I'm conservative on social issues, but I'm liberal on economic
issues," Howard said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
He is indeed conservative on social issues, including gun
control and family values, but on those issues such as Asian
immigration and whether Australia should become a republic,
Howard is decades behind the time.
</P>
<P>
He was about eight months late than his former party leader
Malcolm Fraser and other former prime ministers, such as Bob
Hawke, and his ministers in their condemnation of Pauline Hanson's
racist attack on Asian immigration and Aborigines in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
His refusal last year to apologize over the nation's "stolen
generation", referring to tens of thousands of Aboriginal children
forcibly taken away from their homes during 60 years until the
1970s under the white assimilation policies, and his failure to
endorse multiculturalism made him a moral dwarf in the eyes of
Australian ethnic minority groups and many white Australians.
</P>
<P>
Yet, as one of the nation's longest-serving treasurer, Howard
may take some credit for economic reform measures.
</P>
<P>
During the past 25 years, no one else in Australia politics can
match Howard for his championing of economic reform, for the way
in which he has single-mindedly pursued issues such as smaller
government, lower taxation, industry deregulation, more
competition, more freedom for workers, cheaper imports, more
exports and a tougher stance on trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The past two and a half years saw the Howard government cut
9,000 public service jobs in Canberra alone, slash billions of
U.S. dollars in funding for government services, education, and
social welfare, and encourage attempts to break the country's
maritime trade union's monopoly of power over the nation's sea
ports.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks before he called the October 3 federal election, he
announced his long-cherished plan to reform the nation's
60-year-old tax system with a 10 percent tax on goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the tax reform as well as his political life will
be known Saturday as the whole nation goes to the polls.
</P>
<P>
Howard married Janette, a teacher by profession, in 1971. They
have two boys and a girl. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps Up Exploration of Large Oilfields in Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- China is speeding up efforts to
explore simultaneously two large oilfields in the central
part of the Bohai Sea, in a bid to develop an annual crude
production capacity of 4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, president of the China Offshore Oil
Bohai Corp (COOBC), oil to be turned out by the two oilfields --
Qinhuangdao 32-6 and Nanbao 35-2 -- will be piped inland through
the port of Jingtang in Tangshan city, north China's Hebei
province.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield, with 170 million tons of verified
geological oil reserves, is 100 kilometers east of Tanggu in
Tianjin. Presently, 11 wells have been drilled there.
</P>
<P>
Nanbao 35-2 Oilfield lies 20 kilometers south of Tangshan. Four
test wells have been drilled in the oilfield and have identified
geological oil reserves of 70 million tons. Nanbao's reserves have
been estimated at 110 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the two oilfields are only 20 kilometers
apart, making their joint development possible in a 70-sq km
oil-bearing area in the central Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
He said that seven standard platforms will be erected in the
two oilfields, two pipelines laid at the seabed to pump oil
inland, and terminals built in Jingtang Port.
</P>
<P>
About 650 meters of coastline will be requisitioned for
building oil transport berths, he added. The entire construction
will cost 7.29 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The official forecasts that the Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield will
begin production in 2003 and Nanbao one year later. By 2004, the
two oilfields are expected to produce four million tons of oil a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Computer System Helping Shanghai Airport Improve Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Passengers may feel better
at Shanghai's Hongqiao Airport now that a new computer system has
gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
The new system, APPSLCA, is supposed to improve the management
of aviation by processing data in times of trouble and to help
passengers go through necessary procedures.
</P>
<P>
The system was introduced by the U.S.'s Unisys and the Civil
Aviation Administration of China. It has greatly improved the
efficiency of Hongqiao Airport and will be introduced to other
airports in China, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 100 airports and aviation companies in the
world using the system and its use at Hongqiao shows that the
airport's management is approaching international standards,
officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
