<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Sharemarket Slumps to 5-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
hit a new five-year low Friday with the NZSE40 Capital Index
falling to 1,668 points.
</P>
<P>
This means the index has lost nearly 1,000 points since it
reached its post-crash peak on October 23 last year.
</P>
<P>
In total, the top 40 shares were worth 37 billion NZ dollars
(18.5 billion U.S. dollars) Friday, about 22 billion NZ dollars
(11 billion U.S. dollars) less than their combined market value in
October last year, According to Television New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10 billion NZ dollars (five billion U.S. dollars) has
been wiped off the value of New Zealand shares in the past three
months, The Dominion reported.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper noted that the dive in the
sharemarket in the past three months is unusual, as it came at a
time of falling interest rates, which are usually positive for
equities as investors take their money out of banks and place it
in shares, looking for better returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
