<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Criticizes U.S. for Lamb Import Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government
would oppose any moves by the United States to introduce quotas or
additional tariffs for lamb imports, New Zealand Minister for
International Trade Lockwood Smith said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to a statement issued by Meat New Zealand
expressing concern about a petition filed Thursday by the American
Sheep Industry Association with the U.S. International Trade
Commission seeking a "safeguard action" against what they said
were the damaging price effects of Australian and New Zealand lamb
imports.
</P>
<P>
In a media statement, Smith said the New Zealand Government
would "strongly oppose any move by the U.S. to move in the wrong
direction, particularly with respect to access for an important
New Zealand product like lamb."
</P>
<P>
He said New Zealand would respond positively if the U.S.
Administration initiates consultations with it with respect to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by Meat New Zealand, in the
nine months to June 30 this year, New Zealand sent meat worth
122.3 million NZ dollars (61.5 million U.S. dollars) to the U.S.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
