<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel complained at the
opening ceremony of the parliament that despite Turkey's repeated
warnings and peaceful initiatives, Syria was trying to provoke
the Arab world against Ankara by using Turkey's close ties with
Israel as a pretext.
</P>
<P>
Demirel pointed out that "This is not a friendly attitude. I
declare to the world that our patience is running out and we
retain the right to retaliate against Syria".
</P>
<P>
Turkey accuses Syria of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz declared that former
Mafia leader Allattin Cakici, who was arrested in France two
months ago, had supporters even in the army, the police
headquarters and the national intelligence of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He added that "gangs have spread their branches everywhere. We
have learned that there were gang leaders who attempted to
mediate the appointment of army generals."
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey is to recall its Ambassador to Italy Inal Batu in
protest of the Italian Parliament's permission for "Kurdish
Parliament in Exile," outlawed in Turkey, to hold a two-day
meeting there.
</P>
<P>
Batu is to return to Ankara Monday for "consultations" with the
Turkish high-ranking officials in a bid to study the recent
developments at the Italian Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
