<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Objectives Outlined for NZ's Chairing of APCE 99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Jenny Shipley
has outlined four broad strategic objectives for New Zealand's
chairing of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum in
1999.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued Friday by the New Zealand
Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade, these objectives are:
</P>
<P>
-- Make further substantive progress towards trade and
investment
</P>
<P>
liberalization and facilitation;
</P>
<P>
-- Shape a credible response to the economic crisis;
</P>
<P>
-- Reinforce the capacity of institutions and human resources
in
</P>
<P>
the region to deal with the economic challenges they face;
and
</P>
<P>
-- Build broader support for APEC among the wider community.
</P>
<P>
There are less than three months to go before New Zealand
assumes the role as Chair of the APEC process, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a daunting task ahead of us, both in terms of driving
the APEC process forward, and hosting a successful series of
ministerial and officials' meetings, and of course the Leaders'
Meeting, in New Zealand next year," it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Prime Minister Shipley has
appointed an APEC team of cabinet ministers to oversee the
organization of "APEC 99."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister herself will chair the nine-member committee
and will be joined by Treasurer Bill Birch, Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Don McKinnon, Minister for Enterprise and
commerce Max Bradford, Minister for International Trade Lockwood
Smith, Minister of Maori Affairs Tau Henare, Minister for Food,
Fibre, Biosecurity and Border Control John Luxton, Minister for
the Environment Simon Upton, and Minister of Police Clem Simich.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade will act as its
secretariat, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministerial APEC Committee is due to hold its first meeting
on October 5, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
