<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong Area Attracting Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Pudong New Area
has become a major tourist destination, with 1.88 million tourists
in the first seven months of the year, and 590 million yuan in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Since it was established in 1990, the area has built more than
300 highrises, including dozens of skyscrapers such as the Pearl
TV Tower, the tallest tower in Asia, and the Jinmao Building. Many
of them have become scenic spots that can give visitors a
bird's-eye view of the city.
</P>
<P>
The area has worked out a series of tour routes like "cycling
around Pudong," "touring the Shenmei bottling plant" and "visit to
an agricultural development zone."
</P>
<P>
One popular spot is the Sunqiao Modern Agricultural Development
Zone on a 10-sq.km. area, which produces a great variety of
hydroponic crops and attracted 60,000 visitors during the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Dao Shuming, deputy director of the Shanghai Tourism Commission,
predicts that the number of tourists in the area will grow
steadily in the years to come as infrastructure along the Huangpu
River improves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maintains Impressive Housing Development Momentum (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- China has made remarkable
headway in housing construction and completed housing space
totaling 4.2 billion square meters over the past 20 years since
the start of the reform and opening policy.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the country's average urban per capita living space
has grown to nearly 9 sq m, or a 1.4-fold increase over that of
1978 and the figure for rural areas stands at nearly 18 sq m.
</P>
<P>
Housing industry has not only effectively boosted the national
economic development, but also turned out to be a hot spot for
civilian consumption over the past 20 years since the reform and
opening-up policies were introduced.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth in housing development and marked improvements
in the people's housing conditions have been reported, and annual
urban housing construction has surpassed 200 million sq m, with
the figure for rural housing standing at 600 million sq m.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6 billion sq m of urban and rural housing China built
between 1992 and 1997 helped solve housing problems for over six
million households, whose per capita living space was far below
the national average. Some 25 percent of urban households have
been moved into new houses.
</P>
<P>
The "affordable housing project" has been implemented in more
than 200 cities, with the addition of over 25 million sq m of
housing space.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the rapid development of housing cooperatives has
effectively expanded fund-raising channels and has benefited the
low- and medium-income households.
</P>
<P>
Construction departments at various levels have made great
efforts to improve infrastructure facilities, including water
supply, drainage, heating, roads, bridges, highways, tree-planting
and environmental protection systems. Related efforts have greatly
helped improve the people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
And it has become top concern for the Chinese government to
solve housing problems for the citizens, which is regarded as a
major aspect for the Chinese people to lead a well-off life. To
meet the end, the country has worked out a series of preferential
policies to develop the housing sector as a major economic
pillar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maintains Impressive Housing Development Momentum (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deepening and popularization of housing reform, which means
selling houses to citizens instead of distributing houses to them
as material benefits, will play decisive roles in developing real
estate markets. With the changing of attitude toward spending,
more and more citizens will choose to buy houses for themselves.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to boost housing development and reform,
China has introduced commercialized housing, publicly-pooled
housing funds, individual home mortgage loans and a series of
other effective measures.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Housing Development Plan, housing
construction is expected to account for about four percent of the
country's total GNP between 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The housing development plan through 2000 calls for the country
to build a total of nearly one billion sq m of housing, with some
70 percent of the households affordable to well-equipped houses by
the turn of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
