<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Ruling Party Youth Leader Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Ahmad Zahid Hamidi Friday
resigned as Youth Chief of the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO).
</P>
<P>
Announcing his resignation at a news conference here, Zahid
said the decision was final, adding that he had written two
letters to party president Mahathir Mohamad, who is also Prime
Minister, on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Zahid is known as a strong supporter of former deputy prime
minister and finance minister Anwar Ibrahim who was sacked from
the cabinet on September 2 and expelled from UMNO, of which he was
deputy president, a day later. Anwar is now facing 10 charges of
corruption and sodomy in court.
</P>
<P>
Zahid was arrested on September 21 under the Internal Security
Act, a day after Anwar was detained under the same act, and was
freed from detention on September 30, a day after Anwar was
charged in court.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Zahid said his decision to resign was
not due to pressure from any quarters -- whether from the UMNO
Youth executive committee or state or divisional youth chiefs. He
said the decision was in the overall interests of the movement.
</P>
<P>
Zahid, who is also a member of parliament, said he would remain
in UMNO and continue serving the party as a member.
</P>
<P>
Zahid's resignation came after the UMNO Youth executive
committee handed over a memorandum to the UMNO Supreme Council
through party secretary-general Sabbaruddin Chik on September 24
declaring their loss of confidence in Zahid's leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
