<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures (3): Australian Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are some facts
and figures about Australian Parliament:
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth of Australia is governed under a constitution
adopted on July 9, 1900, and came into force on January 1, 1901.
</P>
<P>
The British Queen is the Head of State of The Commonwealth of
Australia. Executive power is vested in the British Queen, and
exercised by the Queen's appointed representative, the
Governor-General, who normally acts on the advice of the Federal
Executive Council, led by the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Parliament consists of the monarch, represented by
the Governor-General, a 76-member Senate and a 148-member House of
Representatives. It holds the legislative power of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is composed of 12 senators from each state (6
states), 2 each from the Northern Territory and the Australian
Capital Territory.
</P>
<P>
The senators are elected by a system of proportional
representation for six years when representing a state, with half
of the seats renewable every three years, and for a term of three
years when representing a territory.
</P>
<P>
As 1998 election is the standard half-Senate election, only 40
will be contested (The four territory seats are held for a
three-year term and are contested each time there is a House of
Representatives election).
</P>
<P>
Members of the House of Representatives are elected by the
universal adult suffrage and voting is compulsory. The duration of
a House member's term is limited to 3 years. To be nominated for
election to the House of Representative, a candidate must be 18
years of age or over, an Australian citizen, and entitled to vote
at the election or qualified to become an elector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures (1): Election Day, Number of Voters, Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are some facts
and figures about Saturday's federal election in Australia:
</P>
<P>
Polling day: October 3.
</P>
<P>
Number of ordinary polling places: 7,775. The polling places
are usually in local schools, church halls or public buildings and
are open between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. (22:00 GMT Friday and 08:00 GMT
Saturday).
</P>
<P>
Number of ballot boxes: 38,212.
</P>
<P>
Number of voters: 12,056,625 (18 years old or older), compared
with the nation's population of 18.5 million.
</P>
<P>
At stake are all of the 148 seats in the House of
Representatives, and 40 seats or half of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,435 candidates, including 329 for the Senate and
1,106 for the lower house, have nominated for the federal
election.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,435 candidates, 400 are female and 1,035 are male.
</P>
<P>
Preferential voting:
</P>
<P>
Under the preferential voting system, voters are required to
rank candidates in order of preference on the ballot papers. To be
elected, a candidate must achieve an absolute majority, that is at
least 50 percent plus one of the formal votes, either on first
preference or following distribution of preference votes.
</P>
<P>
In other words, If no candidate has more than half of the
votes, the candidate with the fewest votes is excluded. This
excluded candidate's votes are transferred to the other candidates
according to the second preferences shown by voters on the ballot
papers.
</P>
<P>
This process of excluding candidates one by one, continues
until one candidate has more than half the total votes and is
declared elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
