<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures (6): Australian History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following is a brief
introduction about Australian history:
</P>
<P>
The British made their first appearance in Australia in 1688.
British navigator James Cook sighted and made a visit to the
southern shore of the Australian mainland in 1770. In 1786 the
British government decided to colonize the continent, which led to
a great immigration afterwards. The first group of immigrants,
numbering 1,030 (including 736 convicts in exile), under Captain
Arthur Phillip, reached the east coast near Sydney and established
the first colony there. The continent was named "Australia" in
1817. By the end of the 19th century, six colonies had been set up
in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The British Parliament adopted "The Constitution of the
Commonwealth of Australia" in 1900. In the next year, the six
colonies became States and were federated as a self-rule
territory, under the name of the Commonwealth of Australia. On May
9 in the same year, the first session of the Australian Parliament
convened in Melbourne. The Capital was moved to Canberra in 1927.
Under the "Westminster Bill" passed by the British Parliament in
1931, Australia gained the right to act independently in the
domestic and foreign area, and was claimed as independent state in
the Commonwealth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
