<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not Aware of Iranian Move: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A Foreign Ministry spokesman
said the Pakistani government was not aware of the Iranian move to
withdrawal its embassy staff, and was still verifying the facts,
the Frontier Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Iran has reportedly pulled out more than 60 functionaries of
its embassy in Islamabad this week, including some senior
diplomats, because of "certain problems."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmud Mohammadi said in
Tehran that the staff had been withdrawn due to "certain
problems." But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
However, he insisted that there was no change in the state of
relations between the two Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian ambassador to Pakistan, Mehdi Ali Akhundzadeh, told
a Lahore-based newspaper Wednesday that the Pakistani government
had not been informed of the move because the withdrawal did not
come about under duress.
</P>
<P>
He said that since most embassy personnel were feeling unsafe
following the Mazar-i-Sharif incident, they left Pakistan
temporarily to reunite with their families in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Nine Iranian diplomats were killed in the northern Afghan town
of Mazar-i-Sharif when the Taliban militia raided and captured the
town on August 8.
</P>
<P>
However, the Frontier Post quoted a highly-placed Pakistani
source as saying that the Iranian withdrawal "has nothing to do
with the situation in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian decision to cut the embassy staff was linked more
to the situation obtaining in Pakistan, the source said.
</P>
<P>
"An increased threat of sectarian killings, and some recent
newspaper reports may be responsible," the source added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a high-level meeting was held at the Foreign Office
here Thursday to review the situation arising from the withdrawal
of Iranian diplomats from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Sources were tight-lipped about the meeting, and refused to
divulge details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
