<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says NATO Ready to Strike Serbian Forces in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was ready
for military strikes against Serbian forces in Kosovo, but hoped
the crisis would be resolved through diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"The combined threat of the use of force and diplomacy is the
best way of proceeding," Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said after key national security officials briefed most of the
Senate on the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Albright told reporters that the three-track response to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on the Kosovo issue involved
resolving the humanitarian problems, pushing for a diplomatic
resolution and preparing for a NATO strike.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of a credible military threat is to indicate that
in absence of meeting those demands, he faces such a threat,"
Secretary of Defense William Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger and Cohen
delivered the classified briefing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the U.S. warned Americans to leave
Yugoslavia because of the looming air strike against Serbia by
NATO.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said the travel warning
was being issued because "we think the combination of President
Milosevic's failure to respond and the possibility of NATO action
makes Serbia-Montenegro a more dangerous place."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Yugoslavia
must quickly withdraw its forces from Kosovo to avert a looming
military strike by NATO.
</P>
<P>
Asked if it was possible for Milosevic to avert the air
strikes, McCurry said diplomatic possibilities for resolving the
issue had not been exhausted, and it would not be out of character
for Milosevic to yield to United Nations demands that he end
hostilities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"When faced with diplomacy backed by force, he has in the past
backed down," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
