<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researchers Find Links Between Electric Fields, Leukemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Extremely low-frequency
electric and magnetic fields, such as those emitted by residential
appliances and local power lines, may be linked to children's
leukemia, according to a study by a group of U.S. government
researchers.
</P>
<P>
Their report has been on the Web site of the U.S. National
Institute of Environmental Health Sciences (NIEHS). The report was
released Wednesday at a San Francisco presentation by the
institute, which will hold a hearing in the city to record public
comment, San Francisco Chronicle reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Electricity has been used for 100 years without society being
aware of any adverse health effect, other than thermal injury and
electrocution, the report said in explaining the origin of the
study.
</P>
<P>
But a 1979 report first suggested that children living near
power lines had an increased risk for developing cancer, arousing
growing concern on the part of the public about whether electric
and magnetic fields (EMF) might be adverse to human health.
</P>
<P>
Despite a multitude of studies, the report said, there remains
considerable debate over what, if any, health effects result from
exposure to EMF.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the U.S. National Academy of Sciences stated in a
report that "average magnetic fields measured in the homes of
children have not been found to be associated with an excess in
childhood leukemia."
</P>
<P>
By contrast, the new report of the NIEHS, titled "Assessment of
health effects of exposure to power-line frequency electric and
magnetic fields," stated that data "support an association between
exposure to calculated magnetic fields and the incidence of
childhood leukemia."
</P>
<P>
Nineteen of 29 researchers in the NIEHS group voted to conclude
that EMF should be considered "a possible human carcinogen," the
third-highest category of risk. None concluded that EMF should be
classified as a "known human carcinogen," the highest category, or
"probable human carcinogen."
</P>
<P>
In a separate vote, a majority of the researchers concluded
there is "limited evidence" that EMF is carcinogenic in children,
while others found the evidence regarding child leukemia to be
"inadequate."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the researchers concluded overwhelmingly that
there is inadequate evidence that residential EMF exposure is
carcinogenic in adults.
</P>
<P>
As noted in the NIEHS study, weak electric and magnetic fields,
which oscillate 60 times per second, are emitted by power lines,
transformers, service wires and electrical panels, as well such
home appliances as electric blankets, water beds, clocks, electric
razors and television.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
