<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, October 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn
Thursday called for "close coordination on economic policies
between Europe and the United States."
</P>
<P>
The Minister made the statement prior to a meeting in
Washington Saturday of finance ministers and central bank
governors of the Group of 7 countries. He said,"The international
situation calls for thorough coordination between governments and
the central banks." (France-Europe-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- The Slovak government has decided to exempt all
imports from tariffs starting October 1, 1998, said a report
reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Slovak reduced its import tariff from 7 to 5 percent on January
1 and again from 5 to 3 percent on April 1. Slovak Finance
Ministry spokesman Josef Mach said the decision was made to meet
the requests of the World Trade Organization, and also a step in
the country's efforts to join the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD). (Slovak Republic-Tariff
Exemption)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said on
Thursday that the Russian government might to take "unpopular
steps" to get out of the current crisis, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
After a government meeting held on Thursday Primakov told
reporters that Russia was counting on the release of a new tranche
of International Monetary Fund, but if it was suspended or
canceled, the government "has to take measures, which may be
rather unpopular." According to him, if the IMF releases a
4.3-billion-dollar tranche, Russia could be able to get out of the
current adverse situation with minimum losses. (Russia-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union annual inflation rate decreased
from 1.5 percent in July to 1.3 percent in August, Eurostat
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
community said that inflation for the 11-nation euro zone also
dropped, from 1.4 percent in July to 1.2 percent in August.
(EU-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean foreign exchange reserves rose to 46.98
billion U.S. dollars in September from the previous month's 45.09
billion dollars, said the Bank of Korea Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The country's usable foreign reserves, excluding deposits at
overseas branches of South Korean banks, amounted to 43.37 billion
dollars at the end of September this year, up 2.02 billion from
August. The central bank attributed the rise of foreign exchange
reserves to loan repayments of 1.62 billion dollars by commercial
banks and the seventh installment of funds of 640 million dollars
from the International Monetary Fund (IMF). (SKorea-Foreign
Reserves)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- NationsBank and BankAmerica Wednesday announced
that they formally completed their merger, creating the largest
bank in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Starting October 1, customers of both banks can use nearly
14,000 of the banks' ATMs around the country to make cash
withdrawals or transfer funds between primary checking and savings
accounts with no ATM fees, the new bank said in a statement.
Beginning October 1, the merged company's shares will be listed on
the New York and Pacific stock exchanges as BankAmerica
Corporation under the ticker symbol BAC. The shares are also
listed on the London and Tokyo exchanges. (US-Bank Merger)
</P>
