<HEADLINE> Thailand's Cumulative Cash Deficit Under IMF Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's cumulative cash
deficit for fiscal 1998 totaled 115.58 billion baht (2.88 billion
U.S. dollars), just under the 117 billion baht (2.9 billion U.S.
dollars) limit set by the International Monetary Fund, according
to the Thai Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Revenues for the fiscal year that ended on Wednesday totaled
727.51 billion baht (18.1 billion U.S. dollars), versus
expenditures of 835.57 billion baht (20.8 billion U.S. dollars),
leading to a deficit of 108.06 billion baht (2.7 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Extra-budgetary accounts showed a deficit of 7.52 billion baht
(188 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Disbursements totaled 687.1 billion baht (17.1 billion U.S.
dollars), or 82.8 percent of the 830 billion baht budgeted.
</P>
<P>
Pisit Leeahtam, deputy finance minister, was quoted by the
Bangkok Post as saying it was the highest disbursement rate since
1990. The ministry had set a target rate for the year of 82
percent.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 fiscal year deficit target was 3 percent of GDP. The
same target will be maintained for fiscal 1999, with additional
spending directed to help ease the impact of the recession on the
poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
