<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Inflation Amounts to 5.1 Percent in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's September inflation rate
amounted to 5.1 percent, 3.8 points more than that of August,
according to figures published Thursday by the Institute of
Statistics and Census of Ecuador (INEC).
</P>
<P>
INEC reported that the inflation rate was 3.8 percent in the
coastal area and 6.5 percent in the mountain area.
</P>
<P>
It said the country's inflation rate in the first nine months
of this year stood at 31 percent and 37.8 percent for the past 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Prices of gas registered the biggest increase in September --
353.8 percent, while food prices went up by 9.1 percent, urban
transportation 17.3 percent, and a taxi ride 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other goods whose prices increased were gasoline, 15.6 percent;
secondary school fees, 24.8 percent; primary school fees, 14.7
percent, and chicken, five percent.
</P>
<P>
INEC Director Johny Cevallos attributed the inflation rise to
the increase in the prices of the family basket, a consequence of
the economic package of the government announced on September 14.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts predicted that 1998 would end with a price
rise of between 43 and 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund ranked Ecuador's inflation as
the second highest in Latin America, behind Venezuela's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
