<HEADLINE> Czech, Poland to Cooperate Closely Before Joining NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prague, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic and Poland
have agreed on Thursday to step up preparation for joining the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The two countries came to the agreement at a brief meeting held
in the northern Czech city of Liberec on Thursday attended by
Czech Foreign Minister Jan Kavan, Defense Minister Vladimir Vetchy
and Polish Foreign Minister Bronislav Geremek and Defense Minister
Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting the ministers briefed each other on the
progress made by their countries in preparation for joining NATO,
and discussed future cooperation in the political and military
fields.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that after joining the NATO, neither is there
any need for nuclear weapon to be deployed, nor that for foreign
troops to be stationed in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Before the end of the meeting, the two countries concluded a
treaty of confidentiality in an effort to further promote the
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic and Poland, the first countries to be
included into the NATO in its eastward expansion, started their
ministerial meeting in 1995 and have made it an annual event. The
last meeting was held in Vratislav, Poland, in May 1997. 
</P>
