<HEADLINE> Thailand to Allow Foreign Labor in Only Six Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Employment of foreign labor in
Thailand is to be allowed in only six industries under the Labor
Ministry's policy to push foreigners back home, according to Labor
Minister Trairong Suwannakhiri.
</P>
<P>
A sub-committee Thursday agreed not to allow more alien
employment after it had permitted fisheries operators in 22
provinces, cane growers in five provinces, swine raisers in 11
provinces, rubber growers in 12 provinces, and shippers in Bangkok
to continue hiring foreign workers for another year.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Ministry will from now on adopt aggressive policies
against the use of foreign labor and will not renew some foreign
laborers' work permits which will expire next month, Trairong was
quoted Friday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy prime minister Bhichai Rattakul said if the
government was lenient with the employment of foreign workers, its
policy to push illegal immigrants back home would never be
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that Thailand still needs to import
workers from other countries for some industries, saying his
sub-committee will order concerned agencies to work out
regulations on the import of foreign labor. 
</P>
