<HEADLINE> France Urges Close US-European Economic Coordination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- French Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn Thursday called for "close coordination on economic
policies between Europe and the United States."
</P>
<P>
The minister made the statement prior to a meeting in
Washington Saturday of finance ministers and central bank
governors of the Group of 7 countries.
</P>
<P>
"The international situation calls for thorough coordination
between governments and the central banks," he said in a
communique.
</P>
<P>
He added that France has tabled to its partners a memo
outlining two goals.
</P>
<P>
They are: to overcome the current crisis by close coordination
in economic policies between Europe and the United States for
sustained growth, build up security for the financial systems, and
aid under the the International Monetary Fund the new emerging
countries for their stability and economic reform in the short
term; and, in the middle term, to draw up international
regulations so as to create a new "Bretton Woods" agreement to
update the existing world monetary and financial system
established at a UN conference in 1944. 
</P>
