YANGON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar delegation is due to
attend the Eighth Ministerial Economic Cooperation Meeting of Six
Countries in the Mekong Region to be held in Manila, the
Philippines later Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar delegation, led by Minister at the Office of the
State Peace and Development Council Brig-Gen. Abel, is expected to
join in further discussions on projects being implemented by the
six countries -- Cambodia, China, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the Asian Development Bank, which plays a vital role
in promoting regional economic cooperation, made a proposal for
such cooperation among the six nations in the Mekong Region.
</P>
<P>
The last Ministerial Meeting of the Six Countries in the Mekong
Region was held in Manila in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
The present Manila meeting will be followed by a meeting of
economics ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) which is also expected to deliberate the recommendations
made by an ASEAN Coordination Committee earlier in August on a
possible delay in implementing the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) by
three years because of the economic downturn sweeping the region.
</P>
<P>
At the last meeting of the AFTA Council and ASEAN economic
minister's meeting in Kuala Lumpur in October 1997, Myanmar
presented its list of commodities compiled for tariff reduction
for the establishment of AFTA which is to bring tariffs down to
zero to 5 percent within 10 years after joining AFTA.
</P>
<P>
In Myanmar's final Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT)
packages, there are 2,355 tariff lines (43 percent of its total)
in the inclusion list of products and 2,987 tariff lines (54.6
percent of its total) in the temporary exclusion list.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the AFTA Council meeting that ASEAN would
provide technical assistance to Myanmar as well as Laos, its two
new members, to help them fulfill their obligations for AFTA.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
