<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Way to Socialist Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- When the phrase socialist market
economy was first coined at the 14th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China in 1992, western economists were at odds
to explain how socialism could co-exist with free market economics.
</P>
<P>
However, what China has achieved over the past years provides
the most telling answer to any doubt. Market mechanism has now
become so powerful in the country that it is ruling most sectors
with the exception of industries considered to be of strategic
importance, such as telecommunications, military equipment,
transport and energy.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the prices of 85 percent of all
capital goods and 95 percent of all consumer goods in China are
now regulated by market forces while the number of consumer goods
and capital goods under state control has dropped to 30 items from
more than 1,000 five years ago. About 90 percent of the country's
economic volume is now regulated by the market.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics also indicate that demand and supply is
balanced for 75 percent of all commodities on China's market and
that supply exceeds demand for the remaining 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists attribute the transformation to the development of
diversified economic elements and the reform of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, there had been 28.5 million self-employed
persons and small businesses, and 960,000 private enterprises.
Last year, they contributed 54 billion yuan to tax coffers, a
10-fold increase on 1986, and seven percent of the nation's
total. In some townships, contributions accounted for as much as
60 percent of local government revenues.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment has also poured in to stimulate the market
transition, with the value topping 249.1 billion U.S. dollars for
the past five years alone.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, China has granted increasing amounts of decision
making power to its state-owned enterprises, aiming to make them
profitable.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country adopted a policy to encourage mergers and
bankruptcies of state-owned enterprises. By the end of September,
in 111 pioneering cities, 389 enterprises went bankrupt and 623
merged.
</P>
<P>
The move has involved laying off millions of workers. They are
receiving the first social security payments in China's history
while seeking their new place in society.
</P>
<P>
From 1987 to 1997, the average annual growth rate of China's
economy has been maintained at 9.8 percent, the fastest in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Banks Get One Year to Repay Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie has ordered owners and former owners of the country's
troubled commercial banks to repay obligations to the government
in cash within one year or face stiff legal action, a senior
advisor said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie believed one year was enough for the bankers to raise
the cash to repay the liquidity support provided by the central
bank totaling 141 trillion rupiah (12.8 billion U.S. dollars),
said Frans Seda, a senior presidential economic advisor.
</P>
<P>
The central bank had injected the liquidity support to help
banks meet massive withdrawals by panicked depositors in the wake
of plunging confidence in the industry.
</P>
<P>
"The president has set a one year deadline for the debt
settlement," Frans told reporters after meeting with Habibie on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president would not hesitate to take legal action against
those who fail to meet the deadline, Frans was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Bambang Subianto on Tuesday shocked the
banking community by demanding that faulty bank owners repay their
debts in cash, not in fixed-assets, ordering them to submit their
asset disposal plans within a month.
</P>
<P>
But some newspapers reported the next day that the government
would give the delinquent bank owners five years to settle their
debts, triggering a firestorm of criticism that the government was
capricious in its drive to recoup the taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Ginandjar Kartasasmita said Thursday: "We all want this problem to
be over as soon as possible. The government wants its money to be
returned quickly and I assume the bank owners to too, because the
interest rate charged on them is very high."
</P>
<P>
He said the bank owners would continue to be banned from
overseas travel until they settled their obligations.
</P>
<P>
The government originally set September 21 as the deadline for
the owners and former owners of 14 troubled banks to return the
liquidity support. Eight banks failed to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Before September 21, the government had also warned that owners
of banks failing to meet the deadline would face criminal charges.
However, no action has been taken against owners of the eight
banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
