<HEADLINE> Slovak Republic Exempts All Imports from Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Slovak government has decided
to exempt all imports from tariffs starting October 1, 1998, said
a report reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time this year Slovak adjusted its import
tariff, a move mostly welcomed by the European Union and central
and eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
Slovak reduced its import tariff from 7 to 5 percent on January
1 and again from 5 to 3 percent on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Slovak Finance Ministry spokesman Josef Mach was quoted as
saying the decision was made to meet the requests of the World
Trade Organization, and also a step in the country's efforts to
join the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECD).
</P>
<P>
The 29-member OECD was formally established on September 30,
1961, with its headquarters in Paris. The Czech Republic joined
the organization on November 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, economists here warned that the tariff exemption would
lead to further increase of the country's trade and financial
deficits in the near future, and national revenue would suffer a
loss of hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
