<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Working on Brief Impeachment Inquiry on Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Democrats in the U.S House of
Representatives are drafting a proposal for a brief impeachment
inquiry restricted to President Bill Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Several officials said the Democratic proposal, designed as an
alternative to the open-ended inquiry envisioned by Republicans,
may refer to censure as an eventual resolution of the case against
Clinton, but this would come into play only after a formal
investigation, according to an Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
The party's leader in the House, Representative Richard
Gephardt, has suggested timetables of 30 or 60 days, but Democrats
have made no final decisions.
</P>
<P>
Republicans are said to be certain to prevail, both in the
Judiciary Committee as well as in the full House, when they seek
passage next week of an open-ended inquiry based on precedents
established during the Watergate investigation a quarter-century
ago.
</P>
<P>
But Gephardt and other Democratic leaders have been working in
recent days on an alternative that their rank-and-file could rally
behind, thus enabling many of them to vote in opposition to the
Republican proposal without exposing themselves to election-year
charges that they sought to ignore evidence against the president.
</P>
<P>
"This cannot be a never-ending fishing expedition,"
Representative John Conyers, the senior Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, told reporters at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The American people should know that when the Republicans vote
for an open-ended inquiry next week, that they are committing all
of the country to a process that could last for months, for years
-- who knows."
</P>
<P>
Republicans were quick to responded.
</P>
<P>
Representative Charles Canady, for one, responded, "I have a
growing suspicion that no matter what we do... they will criticize
it."
</P>
<P>
"So one day they want us to follow the Watergate model. The
next day they say, 'Don't follow the Watergate model.'"
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Representative Henry Hyde, a Republican and
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, announced plans for an
inquiry, unlimited in time or scope, with Democrats receiving
limited ability to subpoena their own witnesses and the White
House allowed representation at proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Democrats responded Wednesday with strong criticism, as Conyers
and White House spokesman Mike McCurry said that whatever
Clinton's transgressions with Lewinsky, they fell far short of the
offenses Richard Nixon committed.
</P>
<P>
Republicans want to make it possible to bring issues unrelated
to Lewinsky into the investigation. These include several areas
that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr has been investigating, as
well as other topics such as alleged violations of campaign
fund-raising laws during Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
Leading Beijing-based newspapers like "People's Daily" carried
articles on celebrations in various localities marking the 49th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China was filled with jubilation yesterday as people from
all walks of life and from various localities celebrated the 49th
anniversary of the founding of new China.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10,000 people from various ethnic groups in Lhasa,
Tibet, gathered in the square of Potala Palace to celebrate the
49th anniversary of the motherland by holding a grand ceremony of
hoisting the national flag.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region held a grand
reception in the conference and exhibition center to mark the
49th anniversary of the People's Republic of China. China's
stability and growth has contributed to the development of the
entire world, Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong SAR,
said in his message issued here for China's National Day yesterday.
</P>
<P>
 "Beijing Morning Post"
</P>
<P>
-- Over 200,000 people gathered in Tiananmen Square before
sunrise Thursday morning to watch the flag-raising ceremony.
</P>
<P>
China traditionally holds special flag-raising ceremonies
on special occasions and on important national holidays.
</P>
<P>
Central authorities commended dozens of people upon their
heroic deeds in fighting floods, which is part of this year's
National Day celebrations. Those people joined others in watching
the flag-raising ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Beijing Municipal Government marked China's National Day
with a reception attended by more than 500 overseas Chinese,
people from the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, and
compatriots from Macao and Taiwan and friends of Chinese origin
from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said Beijing has witnessed profound
changes over the past 49 years since the founding of the People's
Republic of China, especially over the past 20 years of reform and
opening-up.
</P>
<P>
Jia expressed the hope that overseas Chinese, people in Hong
Kong and compatriots from Macao and Taiwan, as well as foreign
friends of Chinese origin will provide further support for the
city's development. 
</P>
