<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Lower Interest Rates Gradually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
continue to gradually lower interest rates of Bank Indonesia
Certificates (SBI), the Indonesian Observer said Friday, quoting
Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril Sabirin.
</P>
<P>
"The average interest rate resulting from SBI weekly auctions
in the past one month has fallen to around 64 percent from an
earlier high of 72 percent. We will continue to reduce the rates
for as long as possible," Sabirin said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian central bank has maintained its unpopular high
interest rate policy in a bid to contain inflation and help
stabilize the rupiah, which has lost about 80 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's corporate sector has urged the government to lower
interest rates. The plight of the sector has been exacerbated by
the slide in the value of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the government intervenes in the market to influence
the exchange rate by balancing both supply and demand of the
rupiah. The monetary authority also sets the interest rates to
counteract movements in exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin declined to elaborate on the extent of the decline,
saying it will depend on the decrease in the prices of basic
commodities.
</P>
<P>
"We have to control inflation and we have to stabilize the
prices of the basic foods," he said.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation stood at 69.12 percent for the first
eight months of this year. The Central Statistics Agency has
predicted that the inflation rate for the whole year would reach
as high as 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government cannot drastically lower the interest rates as
it would trigger speculation in the market, Sabirin told reporters
after meeting with President B.J. Habibie Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Lowering the SBI interest rate drastically could lead to
speculation which will consequently worsen the economic
situation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
