<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Agriculture Production Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's agriculture
production is expected to drop by 1.65 percent this year compared
with last year, the Brazilian Geography and Statistics Institute
(IBGE) said in a report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This year's total agricultural production will be 76,237
million tons, compared with 77,517 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Because of the drought caused by El Nino phenomenon,
agriculture production in the northeastern region has dropped by
41.5 percent, and the northern and southeastern regions by eight
and 11 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
But the southern region, which yields half of the national
production, has increased its output by 6.5 percent, and the
center-west region registered a three percent growth.
</P>
<P>
The products registering increases are cotton, with 43.8
percent, soybeans, 18.3 percent, and wheat 10.7 percent, while the
biggest reductions are for rice and corn, 16.4 percent and 19.8
percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
