<HEADLINE> Tyson Attorneys Try to Keep his Psychiatric Records Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson's attorneys tried
to persuade the court to keep the former heavyweight champion's
psychiatric records private Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A lawsuit filed in Nevada states court asked that records from
Tyson's examination last week by a team of psychiatrists at
Massachusetts General Hospital be given only to Nevada boxing
authorities and not released to the media or general public.
</P>
<P>
A hearing was scheduled for late Thursday afternoon on a
motion seeking that the records be sealed.
</P>
<P>
"No person wants their medical or psychological records
entered as public exhibits," Tyson attorney Jim Jimmerson said.
"Records that speak to a person's mental fitness are inherently
confidential. They wouldn't normally ever be disseminated to the
public."
</P>
<P>
Tyson's doctors still haven't complied with a directive from
the Nevada Athletic Commission to deliver results from the test
to the commission. 
</P>
