<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researchers Link Fetal Blood Clots, Cerebral Palsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Cerebral palsy can be
triggered by infections and blood clots in the fetus, according to
a research published in the October issue of Annals of Neurology.
</P>
<P>
The research, conducted by a group of U.S. scientists, found
telltale signs of such infections and blood clots by tracking down
certain chemicals in the blood of babies who later were diagnosed
with cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
New evidence will not immediately lead to treatment, diagnosis
or prevention, the magazine's report said, but provides important
clues into the secrets of this mysterious disease.
</P>
<P>
The research was led by Karin Nelson, a child neurologist at
the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke. His
group analyzed newborns' blood samples that were preserved by the
California Birth Defects Monitoring Program. The samples came from
96 children, now 13 to 16 years old, of whom 31 had cerebral
palsy.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found clear differences between their blood and
the blood of healthy children. In the blood from children with
cerebral palsy, chemicals called cytokines were found. The
chemicals are triggered by the immune system in response to an
infection or blood clots, and they also play a key role in fetal
brain development.
</P>
<P>
Nelson suggests that although the body produced the cytokines
to fight off infection, high levels of the chemicals send the
developing brain haywire, causing cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
Cerebral palsy affects about half a million Americans, the
researchers said. Recent studies show about two children per 1,000
are born with the disorder. It is incurable and its complications
become progressively disabling. Its symptom is movement and
posture problems and it also causes mental retardation and affects
hearing and sight.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PSG Stunned, Chelsea, Lazio Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Paris St Germain had shock first
round exit from the European Cup Winners' Cup with a defeat to
Israel's Maccabi Haifa on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Alon Mizrahi scored Haifa's last-gasp goal to give the
Israelis a dramatic 3-2 win on the night for a 4-3 aggregate
victory over the 1996 winners from France.
</P>
<P>
Holders Chelsea and Italy's Lazio survived awkward away
fixtures to creep into the second round, but English club
Newcastle and Germany's MSV Duisburg were both knocked out.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea ground out a 0-0 draw at Swedish side Helsingborg to
go through to the last 16 on the back of their 1-0 victory at
Stamford Bridge a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
Gianluca Vialli's team defended stoutly but rode their luck
when Helsingborg's Peter Wibran hit a post with a header in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
Big-spending Lazio, who forked out in excess of 100 million
U.S. dollars on new players at the start of the season, drew 2-2
in Switzerland at Lausanne Sports to progress on the away goals
rule following their 1-1 draw in the first leg.
</P>
<P>
In pouring rain Chilean Marcelo Salas headed Lazio in front
against Lausanne Sports after just seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
But Lausanne were level within three minutes when Philippe
Douglas, who also scored in the first leg, converted a cross from
the left.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Roberto Mancini then laid a ball back to Sergio
Conceicao who put the Romans back in front after 26 minutes but
Lausanne made Lazio sweat with a second equaliser six minutes
from time by Steffen Renn.
</P>
<P>
In Yugoslavia a second-half penalty was enough for Partizan
Belgrade to clinch a 1-0 home win and a 2-2 away goals aggregate
victory against Newcastle.
</P>
<P>
Midfielder David Batty was again the villain of the piece in
his first full game since missing the decisive spotkick in
England's penalty shooutout defeat by Argentina at the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Batty hauled down Vladimir Ivic in the 53rd minute to give
away the spot kick which Vuk Rasovic duly converted.
</P>
<P>
Genk hammered Germany's representative, MSV Duisburg, 5-0 in
Belgium to go through 6-1 on aggregate. Souleymane Oulare and
Tordur Gudjonsson scored a brace apiece for Genk.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Mallorca drew 1-1 at home to Hearts of Scotland to go
through 2-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
Last year's semifinalists Lokomotiv Moscow of Russia remain on
track after defeating Ukrainian rivals CSKA Kiev in the Russian
capital. Beanpole teenager Dmitry Bulykin scored twice as the
Muscovites won 3-1 to go through 5-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot side Apollon Limassol beat Jablonec of the Czech
Republic on penalties after their tie finished 3-3 on aggregate
after extra-time.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's interest in this season's European competitions
ended when Austria's Ried won 1-0 at MTK Budapest for an easy 3-0
aggregate victory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Besiktas also progressed despite losing 2-1 in Slova
kia to Spartak Trnava. Besiktas won the first leg 3-0.
</P>
<P>
In the UEFA Cup first round, Scotland's Rangers beat Beitar
Jersualem of Israel 4-2 at Ibrox for a 5-3 aggregate win. 
</P>
</TEXT>
