<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Atrocities in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITTED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Thursday evening issued an oral presidential statement
to condemn what was reported as mass shooting of civilians in
Kosovo and called for an immediate probe into the alleged
massacres and bring "those responsible" to justice.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting, which began at 4:30 p.m. (local time)
after "appalling reports" of atrocities in Kosovo since the
council's September 23 resolution, was called by Britain, which,
together with France, has hammered out a draft resolution
proposing "further measures" to solve the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
In an oral statement read to the press after the council
meeting, Jeremey Greenstock, president of the 15-member Security
Council for the month of October, said that "council members
strongly condemned those responsible for the atrocities" in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "called upon (Yugoslav) President
(Slobodan) Milosevic and the Government in Belgrade immediately to
investigate, identify and punish those responsible."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council members recalled "the role of the
International Criminal Tribunal for Yugoslavia, which is empowered
to investigate possible violations of international humanitarian
law in Kosovo," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "the council members made clear their determination
to prevent a major humanitarian catastrophe in Kosovo and to
promote peaceful negotiations," it said,
</P>
<P>
The statement also demanded a full compliance of the September
23 resolution which called for an immediate ceasefire and the
beginning of political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The council members expressed strong hope that U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan will report to the Security Council
the complete compliance of the resolution, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The next week could be decisive in determining whether or not
Western air forces launch massive strikes on Serbian forces. The
full compliance would help avert the planned air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to present his report to the Security
Council, perhaps as early as Monday, on whether the Yugoslav
Government has complied with last week's resolution on Kosovo,
where ethnic Albanians, who formed a majority of the province's
population of 2 million, have been fighting for independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
