<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Launches 1999 International Year of Older Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Calling himself an older
man, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Thursday that he has
seen "the great potential of an age of aging".
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks when launching the 1999 International
Year of Older Persons here. He turned 60 on 8 April 1998. The U.N.
sees a person aged 60 or above as an older one. The theme of the
Year is "towards a society for all ages".
</P>
<P>
The mankind is living in the age of longevity and the aging
trend is changing family structures, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of the 20th century, 20 years have been
added to the average lifespan. Within 30 years, a third of the
population in the more developed countries will be over age 60.
</P>
<P>
And the older population itself is aging, with the share of
the persons aged 80 and above in the aging group expected to grow
to 25 percent by 2050 from about 10 percent now, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The traditional pyramid in which there are many youth and few
elders is giving way to the opposite: an inverse pyramid of one
child, two parents, four grandparents and several
great-grandparents," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief pointed to two features of the "age of
longevity": women are more likely to be care-givers while facing
more risks and developing countries are harder hit by the
problems of the aging society.
</P>
<P>
This is because women are living longer than men and are more
likely than men to be poor in old age. They have to take care of
children, other elder persons and themselves.
</P>
<P>
The other fact is that the majority of older persons live in
developing countries which face the challenges of development and
aging populations simultaneously, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the International Year will enhance public
awareness that older persons are both agents and beneficiaries of
development and that investments in the earlier phases of life are
wise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
