<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Lawyers Circulate Argument to Counter Starr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr lacks evidence to support a major claim in his potential
impeachment grounds against U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Democratic lawyers said in an analysis prepared in advance of next
week's vote on beginning a formal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Starr alleges that Clinton tried to obstruct justice by helping
Monica Lewinsky find a job in New York while the former White
House intern was being asked for testimony in Paula Jones' sexual
harassment case against the president.
</P>
<P>
But lawyers sympathetic to Clinton argue in an unsigned
eight-page report, "The evidence makes it clear that Ms.
Lewinsky's desire to leave Washington arose long before her
involvement in the Jones case, and that the president provided her
only modest assistance."
</P>
<P>
The lawyers, who provided their analysis Thursday on condition
of anonymity, prepared it in advance of next week's House
Judiciary Committee vote on whether not to begin a formal
impeachment inquiry, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky was subpoenaed as a witness in the Jones case on
December 19, 1997. A letter included in the Starr report's
appendices showed that she wrote to the president on July 3 of
that year stating: "I'd like to ask you to help me secure a
position in NY beginning 1 December."
</P>
<P>
Prior to that in 1997, the documents show, Lewinsky told the
president of her repeated efforts to get a job at the White House
after she had been transferred to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
"Had the president intended to ensure Ms. Lewinsky's silence
concerning their relationship, it was surely within his power _ at
any time _ to secure a job for Lewinsky at the White House," the
lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
The attorneys also noted, as other Starr critics have, a
statement that Lewinsky made to Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
"I would just like to say that no one ever asked me to lie and
I was never promised a job for my silence," she said, according to
a court transcript included in the follow-up documents.
</P>
<P>
Starr's office said it would have no immediate comment on the
attorneys' analysis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
