<HEADLINE> Britain's Television Starts Digital Dawn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's digital television age
begins Thursday with the launch of SkyDigital,the digital
television service by satellite broadcaster BSkyB.
</P>
<P>
The Sky service, available on satellite and with over 100
potential channels, is the first of at least three British digital
TV broadcasters trying the digital way of delivering pictures into
homes which will give clearer pictures and CD-quality sound.
</P>
<P>
Britain's terrestrial digital TV service is scheduled to be
launched on 15 November. Cable broadcasters also plan to transmit
digital TV signal early next year.
</P>
<P>
"SkyDigital will transform the way we watch television giving
viewers control. It will revolutionize the way millions of people
spend their leisure time." said BSkyB chief executive Mark Booth.
</P>
<P>
Electrical retailers will begin selling the SkyDigital
set-boxes, the equipment needed to receive digital signal from the
midnight and it is estimated that up to 20,000 units will be sold
in the first 24 hours and 2000,000 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the Sky service is seen as the first stage of a
process that could see the entire country switch to digital with
15 years.
</P>
<P>
Chris Smith, UK's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and
Sport, has said he will monitor the situation closely and decide
when to announce that current analogue television will be switched
off entirely.
</P>
<P>
However, question remains whether the public will quickly be
won over to the attraction of digital TV and there are also doubts
about manufacturers' abilities to supply set-boxes in the
quantities required.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
