<HEADLINE> Rubin Urges Action by All to Solve Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The resolution of the current
financial crisis requires intensified reform efforts by rich and
poor countries, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in New
York Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We must move energetically to meet the immediate challenges of
the crisis and to build a modern architecture for a market-based
system, one that is far less susceptible to systemic instability,"
Rubin told a business audience here.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund must overhaul its operations
and the private banking sector should share its burden too, Rubin
said, adding that Japan needs to "urgently implement strong
effective measures" to cure its banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Rubin's comments came before the IMF-World Bank joint annual
meeting of the 182-nation financial institutions soon to take
place in Washington. The G-7 finance ministers and the central
bank governors are scheduled to meet on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the meeting proposed by President Bill Clinton will
put forward preliminary recommendations based on the outcome of
the work by a working group since February.
</P>
<P>
The working group's report next week would call for increased
openness by the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and individual
countries as a way to alert foreign investors to potential
problems before they reach a crisis stage, he said.
</P>
<P>
The report is expected to also issue suggestions on the
improvement of the international banking supervision and
regulation system, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
