<DOCNO> XIE19981002.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rome Workshop to Focus on Women's Empowerment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The implication of a
rights-based approach to gender equality for the activities of
bilateral and multilateral organizations will be the focus of a
three-day U.N. workshop to take place in Rome, capital of Italy,
on October 5-7, U.N. officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the United Nations Division for the
Advancement of Women of the Department of Economic and Social
Affairs, is expected to review and clarify the understanding and
implications of a rights-based approach to women's empowerment,
advancement and gender equality, taking into account of this
approach in policy and operational considerations.
</P>
<P>
The participants, including gender experts, will elaborate on
a common framework regarding the practical requirement of this
approach in policy development and programming, particularly for
the work of bilateral and multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
It will also assess the role of human rights in women's
empowerment and gender equality.
</P>
<P>
Speakers at the opening session will include Angela E.V.
King, special adviser to the U.N. Secretary-General on gender
issues and the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
A rights-based approach to planning and programming is being
advocated by a growing number of the United Nations system. U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, in his proposals on the U.N. reform,
has underlined that human rights are a cross-cutting element that
should be reflected in all policies and programs.
</P>
<P>
Achieving gender equality, a paramount national and global
responsibility for governments and international organizations,
has been reaffirmed at recent U.N. conferences and summits as a
matter of human rights and social justice, and essential for
overall social and economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
