<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Meet in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) met in New York
Thursday for talks reportedly on the issue of missiles.
</P>
<P>
While officials from both countries declined comment at the
start of the talks, expected to last till Friday, U.S. news
reports said the U.S. alleged missile launch by the DPRK on August
31 gained "new importance" in the current stage.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has denied the allegation, saying it was a satellite
it had launched.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Foley said Wednesday that
the launch "represents another step forward in the DPRK's missile
development program and is a matter of great concern to the U.S.
because of its destabilizing impact in the region."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and DPRK had two rounds of missile talks in 1996 and
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
